# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baby-friendly-hospital-initiative
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma is thought to be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Environmental factors include exposure to air pollution and allergens.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Other potential triggers include medications such as aspirin and beta blockers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Diagnosis is usually based on the pattern of symptoms, response to therapy over time, and spirometry lung function testing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma is classified according to the amount of medication required to control symptoms or mechanisms underlying the condition.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] There is no known cure for asthma, but it can be controlled.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Symptoms can be prevented by avoiding triggers, such as allergens and respiratory irritants, and suppressed with the use of inhaled corticosteroids.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Long-acting beta agonists (LABA) or antileukotriene agents may be used in addition to inhaled corticosteroids if asthma symptoms remain uncontrolled.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Treatment of rapidly worsening symptoms is usually with an inhaled short-acting beta2 agonist such as salbutamol, corticosteroids taken by mouth, and oxygen therapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In very severe cases, intravenous corticosteroids and hospitalization may be required.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In 2023, asthma affected an estimated 363 million people worldwide and caused 442,000 deaths.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Most asthma-related deaths occur in low- and lower-middle-income countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma was recognized as early as ancient egypt.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The word *asthma* is from the Greek ἆσθμα (*âsthma*), which means 'panting'.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma causes recurrent episodes of wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and coughing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Symptoms are usually worse at night and in the early morning or in response to exercise or cold air.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Some people with asthma rarely experience symptoms, usually in response to triggers, whereas others may react frequently and experience persistent symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma is often associated with other conditions both within and outside of the respiratory system.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Comorbid medical conditions are more common in severe asthma and can affect the disease severity, symptoms and treatment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Due to the diversity in onset, symptoms, outcomes, and response to treatment, asthma is often considered a syndrome — a collection of signs and symptoms — rather than a single condition.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Historically asthma was classified as being caused by external factors (extrinsic) such as allergens or by internal factors (intrinsic), unrelated to allergies.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Currently asthma is most commonly classified according to severity, control of symptoms, phenotypes and endotypes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) cause airway restriction and have a wide range of overlapping mechanisms and symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The main difference between the two disorders is that in asthma expiratory airflow fluctuates over time while in COPD airflow obstruction is chronic and often increases in severity over time.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma severity is determined on the basis of how much medication is required to control symptoms and exacerbations.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma control is the burden of asthma on an individual such as symptoms and inflammation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Classification of asthma control does not depend on medication usage like severity does, however they often assess similar factors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma control is assessed based on how well the symptoms are being controlled and future risk of consequences of the disorder.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The frequency and severity of symptoms, impairment caused by symptoms, use of rescue inhalers, questionnaires, healthcare usage, and objective tests such as spirometry, FeNO, sputum eosinophils, and hyperresponsiveness studies are used to evaluate asthma control.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma severity is measured based on how difficult the disorder is to treat.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Severity can only be measured once the disorder is under control.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Those with mild asthma may only require as needed medication to treat the disease while those with severe asthma require high doses of medication to gain control over the disorder or may be unable to get their symptoms under control even with medications.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] A phenotype is the way in which a condition presents itself, such as when the disease first starts to affect a person and what symptoms an individual displays.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] An endotype is the mechanisms that underlie the condition.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma is most commonly divided into two endotypes, T2-high and T2-low (non-T2).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Within the two main endotypes there are subpopulations (phenotypes), some of which overlap or can be categorized under both of the two endotypes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The two endotypes are distinguished based on the type of inflammation present, with the type-2 high endotype involving the type 2 immune system response and type-2 low involving type 1 immune system response.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Type-2 high is characterized by increased eosinophils, increased Fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO), or allergens.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Type-2 low asthma is the absence of these inflammatory markers and the mechanisms are not well researched.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The phenotypes included under the type-2 high endotype include early-onset allergic asthma, late-onset eosinophilic asthma, and Aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Type-2 low asthma phenotypes include asthma associated with obesity, neutrophilic asthma, asthma associated with cigarette smoke, and paucigranulocytic asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Occupational asthma can be further split into separate phenotypes, irritant-induced asthma — caused by exposure to airway irritants such as cleaning products and dust — and sensitizer-induced occupational asthma — developed hypersensitivity.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Irritant-induced asthma is a type-2 low phenotype while sensitizer-induced occupational asthma is a type-2 high phenotype.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma-COPD overlap (ACO) currently lacks a consistent definition making it hard to categorize it into either endotype.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] An asthma exacerbation, commonly referred to as an **asthma attack**, asthma episode, or acute severe asthma are episodes of increased symptoms (shortness of breath, wheezing, coughing, chest tightness), and decreased lung function.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Decreased lung function is measured by peak expiratory flow rate (PEF) or forced expiratory volume in 1 second.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Signs occurring during an asthma exacerbation include the use of accessory muscles of respiration (sternocleidomastoid and scalene muscles), chest retractions with breathing, blue colour of the skin and nails, increased heart rate and changes in respiratory sounds.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] An asthma exacerbation is considered mild when there is difficulty carrying out daily activities due to symptoms and a decrease of at least 20% in PEF for over two days.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In moderate exacerbations, oxygen desaturation is mild, there is no use of auxiliary respiratory muscles, and there is a 50% or lower decrease in PEF.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] During severe exacerbations, the person experiencing symptoms becomes restless and may struggle to speak; oxygen saturation drops and there is above a 50% decrease in PEF.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Life-threatening exacerbations cause lethargy and clouding of consciousness.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Brittle asthma is a kind of asthma distinguishable by recurrent, severe attacks.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] However, brittle asthma is best regarded as a historical disease descriptor rather than a distinct diagnostic category.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] While it remains useful for understanding older literature it is no longer routinely used in contemporary clinical practice.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma is caused by a mixture of genetic and external factors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The disease manifests when those with a genetic susceptibility to asthma are exposed to specific environmental factors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Environmental factors can also trigger asthma symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Factors during pregnancy that have been linked to the development of asthma include weight gain or obesity in the mother, stressful pregnancy, smoking while pregnant, the use of certain medications while pregnant and caesarean section.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Early childhood exposure to secondhand smoke, high levels of stress in parents, respiratory infections, and indoor mold or fungi have also been associated with asthma development.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Prenatal or childhood exposure to cigarette smoke increases the likelihood of a child developing asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Children whose maternal grandmother smoked during pregnancy are also more likely to develop asthma, regardless of if their mothers developed asthma or smoked.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Nicotine is believed to be the cause of these effects and nicotine is linked to changes in DNA.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Respiratory tract infections, especially during early childhood or if they are severe and recurring can lead to decreased lung function and subsequent asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Conversely, there has been research suggesting that certain infections during childhood may lessen the risk of developing asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] This theory is known as the "hygiene hypothesis".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Chronic exposure to air pollution increases the risk of developing asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Outdoor air pollution includes nitrogen dioxide and traffic pollution while indoor air pollution includes biomass, pesticides, building materials such as asbestos and formaldehyde, mold, dust mites, cockroaches, and endotoxins.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma is more commonly seen in urban environments than in rural environments.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In those who are affected by allergies, exposure to allergens can trigger asthma symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] However, some research has suggested that early exposure to allergens in childhood may help desensitize individuals from allergies.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Other studies have shown that early exposure may increase risk of allergies and the development of allergies is multifactorial.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Food allergies and atopic dermatitis in early childhood have been associated with an increased risk of developing asthma as a part of the atopic march.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Allergens also play a role in the development of adult-onset asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Adult-onset asthma is caused by relations between genetics, lifestyle factors such as obesity and smoking, and environmental factors such as an urban or rural environment, occupational exposures, and air pollution.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Unlike childhood asthma, which is more prevalent in males, in adults asthma is more prevalent in females.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Over 400 occupational exposure have been linked to asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Exposure to asthmagens, allergens and substances that are known to cause asthma; the amount and length of time that an individual was exposed to the substance; genetics; allergies; and smoking can affect the development of occupational asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma is highly polygenic, with hundreds of common and rare genetic variants of small effect contributing to disease susceptibility, age of onset, and inflammatory phenotypes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Twin studies and family studies support a substantial heritable component, with estimates that roughly half or more of asthma susceptibility is explained by genetics that is further modulated by environmental and epigenetic factors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Large genome-wide association studies (GWAS) and sequencing efforts indicate that risk reflects the cumulative effects of numerous common genetic variants together with a more limited contribution from rare variants, rather than a small number of loci of large effect.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Meta-analyses now report over 200 genome-wide significant susceptibility loci, many mapping to immune and epithelial genes and explaining a measurable, though still incomplete, fraction of heritability.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Pathway analyses consistently highlight type 2 inflammation, epithelial barrier function, and both innate and adaptive immune signalling, including loci near or within IL33, IL1RL1/IL18R1, TSLP, MHC class II, and GATA3.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The chromosome region 17q12–21 remains the most robustly replicated asthma locus, with effects strongest for childhood-onset disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Multiple genes in this region, including ORMDL3 and GSDMB, appear to act primarily through regulatory mechanisms, with gene-environment interactions and age-dependent effects on airway epithelial responses, particularly to early-life viral infections.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Genetic correlation analyses demonstrate substantial overlap between asthma and other atopic disorders such as eczema and allergic rhinitis, as well as with lung function traits.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Multi-trait studies identify shared risk genes across asthma, hay fever, and eczema, supporting partially common pathways involving type 2 immunity and epithelial barrier dysfunction.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Consistent with this architecture, polygenic risk scores (PRS) derived from multi-ancestry GWAS can stratify individuals by asthma risk, with higher predictive performance for childhood-onset than adult-onset disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Individuals in the highest PRS percentiles show several-fold increased odds of childhood asthma, and PRS analyses have helped delineate heterogeneity across asthma–COPD overlap and related comorbid traits, although clinical implementation remains investigational.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Many asthma-associated variants act within regulatory elements, with effects that are highly cell-type specific and modulated by environmental exposures such as allergens, air pollution, and respiratory infections.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma exacerbations are commonly triggered by external factors or underusage of inhaled corticosteroid medications, however exacerbations can be sudden and unexplained.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Triggers for asthma exacerbations include viral respiratory infections, exposure to allergens, food allergies, outdoor air pollution, season changes or back to school season in the fall, lack of adherence to inhaled corticosteroids, and epidemics of severe asthma exacerbations in a community.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The mechanisms underlying asthma and asthma symptoms include spasms in the bronchial muscles, inflammation in the airways, hypersensitive airways, and excessive secretion of mucus in the airways.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma mainly affects medium-sized airways, however small or large airways may also be affected as the condition progresses.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Airway inflammation is consistent across everyone with asthma, regardless of symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The cells involved in the inflammation seen in asthma include eosinophils, neutrophils, CD4 T lymphocytes, mast cells, basophils, macrophages, respiratory epithelium, endothelial, and smooth muscle cells.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Airway inflammation leads to structural changes in the airways, including thickening of the airway smooth muscle and the tissue beneath the lining.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] There is increased tissue and matrix buildup in the airway wall, along with more small blood vessels and nerve fibers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The glands that produce mucus also increase in size.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In asthma, the airways contract more than what is normal in response to both internal and external triggers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] This hyperresponsiveness alongside inflammation affects the nerves in the airways — making them more sensitive — and causes the body to produce too much mucus.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Contraction of airway smooth muscle, swelling (edema), thickening of the airway wall due to remodelling, increased mucus production, and mucus plugs contribute to narrowing of the airways.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Airway hyperresponsiveness is excessive narrowing of the airways in response to stimuli that are normally harmless.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] This narrowing leads to variable airflow restriction and asthma symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Airway hyperresponsiveness is somewhat reversible with treatment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Diagnostic guidelines for asthma vary in regards to what testing should be done to confirm the diagnosis, when to test, and what criteria should be used for the diagnosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The diagnosis cannot be made based on a single test and is instead made based on a combination of symptoms and respiratory function testing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma guidelines advise using objective tests to confirm asthma in people with suggestive symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Respiratory tests such as spirometry, bronchodilator reversibility (BDR) testing, and measuring changes in breathing flow over time (peak flow variability) are included in all major asthma guidelines.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Symptoms of wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and coughing that fluctuate according to time of day and exposure to triggers are characteristic of asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Personal or family history of allergic conditions can also help identify people with asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma rarely presents with physical findings on examination unless the person is symptomatic.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] If someone is medically unwell or displays a high amount of symptoms before the diagnosis is confirmed, medical guidelines recommend treating the person before performing respiratory testing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Global Initiative for Asthma (GINA) guidelines for children above five years of age and adults suggest confirming variable expiratory airflow in those who have symptoms suggestive of asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Variable expiratory airflow in asthma refers to fluctuations in lung function over time.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Variation in lung function can be shown by spirometry testing, peak expiratory flow, or bronchial provocation testing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The most accurate measurement of lung function is spirometry, which tests how much air a person can forcefully breathe out in one second (FEV1), FEV1 is then compared to the total amount of air exhaled after taking a deep breath (FEV1/FVC ratio).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] When testing for asthma, spirometry is performed twice; the first measurements are taken when the patient is not using any asthma medication and the second is taken after the administration of medication.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] An increase of FEV1 after taking asthma medication is indicative of asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] If spirometry is not available then peak expiratory flow can be used to show variable lung function.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] GINA guidelines recommend testing how fast a person can breathe out (peak expiratory flow) twice a day for two weeks.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Daily changes greater than 10% may suggest asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Bronchial provocation testing measures how sensitive and reactive the airways are.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] During the test, substances such as inhaled methacholine, histamine, or inhaled mannitol as well as exercise and controlled rapid breathing are used to try to trigger airway narrowing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] These tests can help identify asthma but are not specific, because airway sensitivity can also occur in other conditions like allergic rhinitis, cystic fibrosis, bronchopulmonary dysplasia, and COPD.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] A negative test result in someone not using inhaled corticosteroids (ICS) can help rule out asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] However, a positive result does not always confirm asthma, so symptoms and other clinical findings must also be considered.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] For adults, NICE guidelines recommend testing fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO) and blood eosinophils as a first step.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] If FeNO or eosinophils are not elevated then they recommend testing bronchodilator reversibility (BDR) with spirometry or peak expiratory flow (PEF) if spirometry is not available.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Finally, if testing remains inconclusive, bronchial challenge tests are recommended.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Guidelines for children ages five to sixteen are similar to the adult guidelines aside from recommendations surrounding blood eosinophil count.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] For children ages five to sixteen NICE guidelines do not recommend blood eosinophil count as an initial test, but instead they recommend measuring blood eosinophil count, skin prick testing for dust mites, or total IgE levels if respiratory testing is inconclusive.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] According to NICE guidelines, children younger than five should be treated for asthma if they have symptoms suggestive of the condition instead of undergoing testing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] GINA has proposed a set of diagnostic criteria for asthma in those under the age of five.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Lack of alternative explanation for symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Response to asthma medication during acute wheezing episodes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Several conditions mimic the symptoms of asthma and the differential diagnosis for asthma varies based on age.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] For older adults the differential diagnoses include medication-related cough, heart failure, lung embolism, interstitial lung disease, central airway obstruction, COPD, bronchitis, gastrointestinal reflux disease, recurrent respiratory infections, heart disease, and vocal cord dysfunction.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Many of the potential differential diagnoses for asthma commonly co-occur with asthma as well.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Other proposed preventative measures such as dietary changes, breastfeeding, supplements, and early exposure to pets or other common allergens do not currently have enough evidence to support their effectiveness.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The goal of asthma management is to reduce symptoms minimize the risk of complications such as exacerbations, reduced lung function, and medication side effects.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] This is done by evaluating asthma control and the risk of exacerbation, providing education and guidance on how to manage the disease, finding triggers and ways to minimize them, and medication.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma control should be reviewed during doctors appointments so that treatment can be adjusted accordingly.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] After a diagnosis of asthma is made the person receiving the diagnosis and their family should receive education about the disease and a plan for management.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Education includes information about avoiding triggers, self monitoring of symptoms or peak expiratory flow, an asthma action plan, asthma control and treatment options.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma action plans include management options to prevent and treat exacerbations as well as how to modify treatment based on symptoms or seek additional medical care.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] School based education programs on how to manage asthma decrease hospitalizations for asthma in school-aged children.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Non-medical strategies to manage asthma consist of avoiding exposure to triggers and management of factors that contribute to asthma severity or symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Exposure to cigarette smoke, from smoking or second-hand smoke, negatively affects asthma control and it is therefore recommended for those with asthma to refrain from smoking and limit exposure to second-hand smoke.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] For those with occupational asthma, it is recommended that sensitizers and allergens at work be avoided.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Due to the variety of potential allergens and the difficulty of eliminating exposure to allergens, current guidelines do not recommend that those with asthma avoid indoor or outdoor allergens.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Certain medications such as Aspirin, beta-blockers, and nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) can worsen asthma symptoms in some individuals.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] It is still considered safe for those with asthma to take these medications, unless they have caused adverse reactions in the past.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Guidelines encourage those with asthma to maintain a balanced and healthy diet due to benefits on overall wellbeing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Regular physical activity is encouraged for those with asthma due to its positive effects on overall health, however, it does not result in any direct improvement in asthma symptoms and no specific form of exercise is more beneficial.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] For some, exercise may trigger asthma symptoms and therefore it is recommended that inhalers be used beforehand.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Pulmonary rehabilitation may be used to increase tolerance to exercise.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Obesity can cause asthma symptoms to be harder to control or cause more severe symptoms, weight loss in obese individuals is therefore recommended.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] There is not enough evidence that dietary changes, including restrictive diets or supplements are helpful in managing asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Alternative treatments such as acupuncture, air ionizers, manual therapies (osteopathic, chiropractic, physiotherapeutic and respiratory therapeutic manoeuvres), and breathing exercises are not recommended by clinical guidelines due to a lack of evidence that they are effective.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Breathing exercises do not decrease asthma exacerbations or improve lung functioning, however they can be used alongside medications to help control symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Medications for asthma are generally divided into three categories, controllers — taken daily to control symptoms, reduce exacerbations and decrease inflammation — relievers — taken as needed for severe symptoms or exacerbations — and additional medications added on to manage more severe asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Medications are prescribed at the lowest dose possible while still treating symptoms and preventing exacerbations.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Devices for inhaled medications include pressurized metered dose inhaler (pMDI), dry-powder inhalers (DPI), mist inhalers and nebulizers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The choice of delivery method depends on the type of medication used, local availability, age, and ability to use the inhaler properly.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] DPIs are difficult for children to use and are therefore discouraged in those under six years of age.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Spacers are used alongside pMDIs to increase the amount of medication inhaled.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The choice of medication used for asthma management depends on symptom control, risk factors, availability, adherence, ability to use the medication, cost and environmental impact.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] It typically takes one or two weeks for symptoms to improve after starting inhaled corticosteroids (ICS) and the response to medication is monitored whenever it is adjusted.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] If asthma symptoms and exacerbations remain well controlled after two or three months, the dosage of medication can be gradually reduced to achieve symptom control at the lowest possible dose of medication.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] If asthma symptoms and exacerbations persist despite two to three months of treatment with ICS factors such as inhaler technique, adherence, exposure to triggers, comorbidities, and alternative diagnoses are assessed before medication dosage is increased.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The first line treatment of asthma for children are ICS, for teenagers and adults guidelines recommend a combined ICS and long-acting beta2 agonist (LABA) inhaler.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] After a diagnosis of asthma is confirmed, ICS are started as soon as possible.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Guidelines also recommend that everyone diagnosed with asthma have access to a reliever inhaler in case of symptom flare ups.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In children younger than five, higher doses of ICS are used to treat persistent symptoms while older individuals may be treated with an additional medication.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Medical guidelines recommend referring people who have persistent symptoms despite adequate treatment to an asthma specialist (usually a respirologist or allergist).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Historically, asthma was treated with short-acting β2 agonists (SABA) as needed and ICS were only used if symptoms persisted.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Due to research suggesting that management with SABA over ICS was insufficient to prevent exacerbations, guidelines now prefer ICS over SABA.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] For those over the age of twelve, if asthma is not well controlled with an ICS/formoterol inhaler then guidelines recommend that medications be taken daily instead of on an as needed basis and gradually increased until symptoms are controlled.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] If higher doses of ICS/formoterol are not enough to control symptoms then there are several different medications that may be added in to help manage asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] These include the leukotriene receptor antagonists (LTRA) montelukast, a mist inhaler containing the LAMA tiotropium, and azithromycin.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In those with sensitization to aeroallergens, allergen-specific immunotherapy can increase tolerance to allergens by slowly introducing the allergen to an affected person.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] This is done through two different methods; subcutaneous immunotherapy — injections — and sublingual immunotherapy — under the tongue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Biologics can be used to reduce inflammation that may play a role in asthma symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Finally, oral corticosteroids or bronchial thermoplasty may be used as last resorts for severe asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In children under the age of five who have comorbid atopic disorders and intermittent asthma symptoms or severe flare-ups a 8-12 week trial of low dose ICS as maintenance treatment and a SABA for flare-ups is recommended by NICE guidelines.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] If symptoms clear up during the trial then medication can be stopped and symptoms are monitored in the following months to watch for returning symptoms or exacerbation, in which case ICS and SABA can be started again.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Persistent symptoms are treated with increasing doses of ICS and an LTRA.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Low doses of ICS for maintenance and SABA as needed are used to manage asthma in children ages six to eleven, with ICS used whenever SABA are needed to treat flare-ups.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] If symptoms persist then the dose of ICS may be gradually increased, a LTRA can be added on top of inhalers or a low-dose ICS-LABA or ICS-formoterol can be used instead of ICS.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Treatment of asthma exacerbations involves several doses of bronchodilators, oral corticosteroids, and oxygen supplementation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Salbutamol (albuterol) is commonly used for treating exacerbations with several doses being administered every couple of hours until symptoms lessen.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] When exacerbations are severe or do not subside with inhaled medications, oral corticosteroids are used and continued for a week after the exacerbation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Oxygen therapy is also used to maintain a healthy oxygen saturation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Ipratropium, a short-acting anticholinergic, can also be used alongside other treatments to manage exacerbations in those experiencing moderate or severe symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Both intravenous magnesium sulfate and helium–oxygen therapy are not recommended by clinical guidelines for the management of exacerbations, however they may be used in those whose symptoms do not react to other first-line treatment options.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Staying with a treatment approach for preventing asthma exacerbations can be challenging, especially if the person is required to take medicine or treatments daily.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Reasons for low adherence range from a conscious decision to not follow the suggested medical treatment regime for various reasons including avoiding potential side effects, misinformation, or other beliefs about the medication.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Problems accessing the treatment and problems administering the treatment effectively can also result in lower adherence.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Various approaches have been undertaken to try and improve adherence to treatments to help people prevent serious asthma exacerbations, including digital interventions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma symptoms usually manifest during early childhood.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Young children commonly experience asthma symptoms following viral infections, however only around half go on to develop asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Children who experience recurring asthma symptoms are more likely to develop airway inflammation and structural changes in the lungs.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] They may also have reduced lung function and are more likely to continue experiencing troublesome respiratory symptoms as they enter adulthood.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Despite asthma being more prevalent in children, mortality rates, morbidity, and usage of healthcare is higher amongst adults.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Over time, the mortality rate of asthma has gone down and it is now considered a rare cause of death.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Estimates from The Global Burden of Disease Study (GBD) collaboration state that over one thousand people die each day due to asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma mortality rates are typically higher in low-income regions due to lack of access to medical care.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The burden of disease is a measure of the overall impact of a disease on health.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] GBD estimates this impact using data on disease prevalence, deaths, and health surveys.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] It measures disease burden through years of life lost due to premature death (YLL) and years lived with disability (YLD).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] These two measures are combined to calculate disability-adjusted life years (DALYs), which represent the total health loss caused by a disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] YLD reflects both the severity of disability and how long it lasts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In 2019, asthma was responsible for an estimated 21.6 million DALYs worldwide across all age groups.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] It was the 34th leading cause of disease burden globally and accounted for about one-fifth of all DALYs related to chronic respiratory diseases.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Nearly half of this burden was due to 10.2 million years lived with disability.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma was also the 24th leading cause of disability worldwide in 2019, with a slightly greater impact on males than females.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In 2023, approximately 363 million people worldwide were affected by asthma, and 442,000 people died from the disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Rates vary between countries, with prevalences between 1 and 29%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] It is more common in developed than developing countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Within developed countries, it is more common in those who are economically disadvantaged, while in contrast, in developing countries, it is more common in the affluent.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The reasons for these differences are unclear.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Low- and middle-income countries make up more than 80% of the mortality.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] While asthma is more common in boys than girls, severe asthma occurs at almost equal rates.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In contrast adult women have a higher rate of asthma than men.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Overall, there is a slightly higher health burden on women than men.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma is more common in the young than in adults.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma was recognized in ancient egypt and was treated by drinking an incense mixture known as kyphi.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] It was officially named as a specific respiratory problem by Hippocrates c.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] 450 BC, with the Greek word for "panting" forming the basis of our modern name.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In 200 BC, it was believed to be at least partly related to the emotions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In the 12th century, the Jewish physician and philosopher Maimonides wrote *Maqāla fī al-Rabw* ("Treatise on Asthma") in Arabic.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In the work, he described the symptoms of asthma, proposed dietary and therapeutic treatments, and emphasized the importance of clean air and climate in managing the condition.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Traditional Chinese medicine also offered medication for asthma, as indicated by a surviving 14th-century manuscript curated by the Wellcome Foundation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] A well-documented case in the 19th century was that of young Theodore Roosevelt (1858–1919).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] At that time there was no effective treatment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Roosevelt's youth was in large part shaped by his poor health, partly related to his asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] He experienced recurring nighttime asthma attacks that felt as if he was being smothered to death, terrifying the boy and his parents.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In 1873, one of the first papers in modern medicine on the subject tried to explain the pathophysiology of the disease while another in 1872, concluded that asthma can be cured by rubbing the chest with chloroform liniment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Medical treatment in 1880 included the use of intravenous doses of a drug called pilocarpine.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Bosworth theorized a connection between asthma and hay fever.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] At the beginning of the 20th century, treatment was focused on avoidance of allergens and the use of selective beta2-adrenergic agonists as treatment strategies.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Epinephrine (adrenaline) was first referred to as a treatment of asthma in 1905.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The asthma was relieved with this treatment by what was described as "vasomotor ataxia of the relaxing variety".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The successful results of using epinephrine provided encouraging medical data on the hypothesis that asthma was due to vasodilation and the subsequent inflammation of the swelling of the bronchial mucosa.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In the 1930s, U.S. physician Alvan Barach created, by means of spirometry, the quantification of expiratory flow rates to nebulized epinephrine for those with asthma, which was the first published medical report on the effectiveness of bronchodilation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] During the 1930s to 1950s, asthma was known as one of the "holy seven" psychosomatic illnesses.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Its cause was considered to be psychological, with treatment often based on psychoanalysis and other talking cures.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] As these psychoanalysts interpreted the asthmatic wheeze as the suppressed cry of the child for its mother, they considered the treatment of depression to be especially important for individuals with asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In the 1940s, the first pure β-agonist to be synthesized was isoprenaline.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Both isoprenaline and adrenaline are catecholamines.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] However, isoprenaline was an effective bronchodilator that was more selective than epinephrine.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The efficacy of anecdotal applications of oral corticosteroids (OCS) for the asthma was published in 1952.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In 1958, the association between a treatment strategy of OCS and a reduction in eosinophils in the sputum was published.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The use of a pressurized metered dose inhaler was developed in the mid-1950s for the administration of adrenaline as well as isoproterenol, and was later used as a beta2-adrenergic agonist.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Inhaled corticosteroids and selective short-acting beta agonists came into wide use in the 1960s.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In 1967, adrenergic receptors were classified into the two subtypes of the β1 and the β2 adrenergic receptors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The β2 adrenergic receptors were found to be dominant in the lungs as well as present in the alveolar airspace.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The discovery of the β2 adrenergic receptors allowed for the discovery and development of beta2 agonists.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Specifically, it allowed for the development of selective β2-agonists starting in the 1960s.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Between 1970 and 1985, the following countries saw a general rise in reported asthma mortality in people aged 5 to 34: Singapore, Australia, Japan, England/Wales, West Germany, Israel, United States, Netherlands, Canada, and France.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Additionally, New Zealand experienced a major epidemic of asthma in this period, which may have been due to inadequate maintenance therapy and long-term management of the disease amongst those affected, as well as delays in receiving care in emergencies.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] As of 2005, more "westernized," urbanized countries had much higher rates of asthma than "less developed" countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] However, exposure to urbanization alone has not been able to explain these disparities.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In the United States, the burden of asthma falls disproportionately on racial and ethnic minorities and economically underprivileged populations.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] As of 2016, the prevalence of asthma was highest in non-Hispanic black and Puerto Rican children.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] The prevalence of asthma was also over 1.5 times higher in Americans 100% below the poverty level than those 450% of the poverty level or higher.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] As of 2021, the mortality rate for black Americans with asthma was two times higher than for white Americans.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Neighborhoods in the United States with predominantly racial and ethnic minority populations are affected to a greater extent than predominantly white neighborhoods by air pollutants, which are a significant factor in the occurrence of asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Additionally, residents of areas that were more likely to be redlined have asthma emergency department visit rates 2.4 times higher than residents of areas that were less likely to be redlined.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] People with asthma often experience reduced quality of life, including fatigue, sleep problems, lower levels of physical activity, and difficulty concentrating.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] These problems can lead to missed days at school or work and can create financial and productivity challenges for families and communities.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Asthma also places a major economic burden on society.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In 2008, the estimated costs of asthma were between $49.36 million and $8,256 million in several high-income countries, including Canada, Germany, Singapore, Switzerland, and the United States.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] A later study found that the total annual cost of asthma in the United States had risen to $81.9 billion by 2013.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] There is less information available from low- and middle-income countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] However, the financial impact is greatest among people with severe or poorly controlled asthma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] In developing countries, people with uncontrolled asthma account for about half of all asthma-related costs, despite making up only 10–20% of people with the disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/asthma] Worldwide, the financial burden of asthma is estimated to be greater than that of tuberculosis and HIV/AIDS combined.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The initiative is a global effort for improving the role of maternity services to enable mothers to breastfeed babies for the best start in life.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It aims at improving the care of pregnant women, mothers and newborns at health facilities that provide maternity services for protecting, promoting and supporting breastfeeding, in accordance with the International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] UNICEF, WHO, and many national government health agencies recommend that babies are breastfed exclusively for their first six months of life.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Studies have shown that breastfed babies are less likely to suffer from serious illnesses, including gastroenteritis, asthma, eczema, and respiratory and ear infections.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Adults who were breastfed as babies may be less likely to develop risk factors for heart disease such as obesity and high blood pressure.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] There are benefits for mothers too: women who don't breastfeed have increased risk of developing heart disease, hypertension, diabetes, high cholesterol, breast cancer, ovarian cancer and hip fractures in later life.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI aims to increase the numbers of babies who are exclusively breastfed worldwide, a goal which the WHO estimates could contribute to avoiding over a million child deaths each year, and potentially many premature maternal deaths as well.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Comply fully with the International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes and relevant World Health Assembly resolutions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Have a written infant feeding policy that is routinely communicated to staff and parents.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Establish ongoing monitoring and data-management systems.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Ensure that staff have sufficient knowledge, competence and skills to support breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Discuss the importance and management of breastfeeding with pregnant women and their families.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Facilitate immediate and uninterrupted skin-to-skin contact and support mothers to initiate breastfeeding as soon as possible after birth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Support mothers to initiate and maintain breastfeeding and manage common difficulties.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Do not provide breastfed newborns any food or fluids other than breast milk, unless medically indicated.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Enable mothers and their infants to remain together and to practise rooming-in 24 hours a day.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Support mothers to recognize and respond to their infants' cues for feeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Counsel mothers on the use and risks of feeding bottles, teats and pacifiers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Coordinate discharge so that parents and their infants have timely access to ongoing support and care.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The program also restricts use by the hospital of free formula or other infant care aids provided by formula companies and recommends that when formula is medically needed, it should be given in a small cup or spoon, rather than a bottle and should only be used to supplement breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2011, approximately 15,000 facilities in more than 152 countries had been inspected and accredited as "Baby-Friendly." The number of accredited hospitals has continued to grow.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2019, a survey found that 28% of the hospitals in the US were registered as Baby Friendly.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The World Health Organization recommends that if a mother is unable to breastfeed, chooses not to breastfeed, or if her baby (often premature) shows signs that it isn't getting enough breast-milk, a healthy wet nurse or milk from a donor is a healthy alternative to formula.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A special formula is manufactured for premature babies, although the World Health Organization recommends it only if breast-milk is medically not an option such as if a premature baby has to be fed formula through a tube to maintain a healthy weight.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The World Health Organization advocates the importance of a baby being close to its mother whenever possible even if the mother does not breastfeed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Canada, the provinces of Quebec and New Brunswick have mandated the implementation of the BFHI.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] All public health units in Ontario have been required to work towards having BFI designation since 2011.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2012, the Ministry of Health and Long Term Care in Ontario added BFI status to their progress indicators for Public Health Units thus requiring all Public Health Units in Ontario to begin implementation of BFI.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Other provinces and territories are implementing strategies at regional and local levels.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2008, 18 health care facilities (9 hospitals & birthing centres and 9 community health services) had been designated "Baby-Friendly" across the country.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Women's Hospital and Health Centre has been recognized as a breast-feeding and "baby-friendly" hospital by the World Health Organization (WHO) and UNICEF since 2008.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It is the largest hospital in Canada to receive the designation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] China, now has more than 6,000 Baby-Friendly Hospitals, exclusive breastfeeding in rural areas rose from 29 per cent in 1992 to 68 per cent in 1994; in urban areas, the increase was from 10 per cent to 48 per cent.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Cuba, 49 of the country's 56 hospitals and maternity facilities have been designated as "baby-friendly".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In the six years following the initiation of the BFHI program, the rate of exclusive breastfeeding at four months almost tripled - from 25 per cent in 1990 to 72 per cent in 1996.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Hong Kong several hospitals have shown interest in being designated Baby Friendly.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] However, only Queen Elizabeth Hospital has advanced past the Award of Level 2 Participation stage and is well on its way to receiving BFHI accreditation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI started in Ireland in 1998 under the auspices of the Irish Health Promoting Hospitals Network (a WHO programme).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI in Ireland became an independent registered charity in mid-2016 and changed their name to Baby Friendly Health Initiative.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Sweden is considered the global leader in terms of BFHI implementation: four years after the programme was introduced in 1993, all of the then 65 maternity centres in the country had been designated "baby-friendly".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2014 78.60% of babies were born in BFHI hospitals.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Between 2001 and 2013, the increase in certified hospitals was from 38 to 176.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The UNICEF UK Baby Friendly Initiative was launched in the United Kingdom in 1995.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Initiative works with the National Health Service (NHS) to ensure a high standard of care for pregnant women and breastfeeding mothers and babies in hospitals and community health settings.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Baby Friendly Initiative accredits health-care facilities that adopt internationally recognised best practice standards for breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] During each stage of accreditation, the Initiative provides support as facilities implement standards relating to policies and procedures, staff education, effective auditing, educating pregnant women and mothers, and other relevant areas.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 1998, its principles were extended to cover the work of community health-care services with the *Seven Point Plan for the Promotion, Protection and Support of Breastfeeding in Community Health Care Settings*.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It has been estimated that if all babies were breastfed, over £35m would be saved by the NHS in England and Wales each year in treating gastroenteritis alone.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Despite that, in 2013 breastfeeding rates in the UK were amongst the lowest in Europe: 78 per cent of babies born in the UK were breastfed at birth, falling to 63 per cent at one week.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Only one in five babies still received breastmilk at six months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2013 the success of the initiative in Scotland showed that 90% of Scottish mothers gave birth in a UNICEF-accredited Baby Friendly hospital.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] This compared to 30% of mothers in England, 58% for Wales and 57% in Northern Ireland.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The first hospitals verified as Baby-Friendly in the US were on the Pacific Coast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The first US hospital to receive this designation was Evergreen Hospital Medical Center, in Kirkland, Washington, which was certified in September 1996.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] All of these early adopters were able to achieve 100% breastfeeding initiation rates.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In New York City, the Harlem Hospital Center was the first hospital to receive the "Baby Friendly" certification granted by Baby-Friendly USA for the city in 2008.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2011, New York University Langone Medical Center became the second hospital to receive the Baby-Friendly Hospital designation in New York City.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Johns Hopkins Hospital in Maryland describes the process of receiving the Baby Friendly designation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2 May 2018, the United States had 512 hospitals that hold the Baby-Friendly designation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] This translates to 24.57% of annual births.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2019, 28% of hospitals in the U.S. have been accredited by the WHO.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] One group of authors expressed concerns in a paper published in October 2016.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It questioned whether full compliance with the ten steps of the initiative might inadvertently lead to the promotion of potentially hazardous practices and/or counterproductive outcomes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Specific concerns described in this paper included increased risk of sudden unexpected postnatal collapse, rigidly-enforced rooming-in practices leading to exhausted or heavily medicated mothers caring for newborns, and an unnecessary ban on pacifier use.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2016 systematic review examined the impact of BFHI implementation on breastfeeding and child health outcomes worldwide and in the United States.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors suggested that following the BFHI Ten Steps had a positive impact on short, medium, and long-term breastfeeding outcomes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] However, they warned their results for the United States explaining "All of the United States BFHI evidence comes from observational studies, the vast majority of which are of very low or low quality.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Although there is consistent empirical evidence that BFHI has led to improvements in breastfeeding outcomes in the very short and short terms, its impact on BF outcomes in the long term remains unclear".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Looking at 58 studies, the review found that community support was the key to long-term sustainability of breastfeeding that was initiated in the BFHI hospital setting.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A study published in the *Journal of Pediatrics* in 2019 showed that increased rates of implementation of the BFHI were temporally associated with a decrease in the rate of infant deaths in the first six days after birth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors said that their findings dispelled the suggestion that hospital-based breastfeeding initiatives might increase infant death from asphyxiation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors did not discuss the other potential harms to mother and baby that critics have raised, such as increased incidence of neonate hospital admission due to dehydration and poor maternal mental health outcomes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2017 study focusing on hospital readmission among infants based on method of feeding raised concerns that exclusive breastfeeding is linked to double the rate of readmission to hospital among neonates as compared to formula feeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Critics of the Baby Friendly Initiative point to this type of data and several anecdotal stories of babies harmed at hospitals following the Baby Friendly Initiative as evidence that the current guidelines are potentially harmful and not meeting the needs of mother or baby.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2021 review of systematic reviews raised further doubts about some of the claims raised in support of the Baby Friendly Initiative, as it was found that the majority of cited studies concluding benefits of implementation were of low or very low quality.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors raised a number of concerns surrounding quantification of long-term outcomes on maternal and child health apart from breastfeeding initiation, and suggested that outcomes may differ substantially among poor and wealthy countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Additionally, the authors described potential negative outcomes associated with full implementation of the Baby Friendly Initiative, including promoting unrealistic breastfeeding expectations, mothers feeling pressured to breastfeed, and increased feelings of maternal guilt.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Further high quality studies were recommended to evaluate both long-term breastfeeding outcomes and other aspects of maternal health.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] About five to ten percent of cases are the result of an inherited genetic predisposition, including *BRCA* mutations among others.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancer most commonly develops in cells from the lining of milk ducts and the lobules that supply these ducts with milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Cancers developing from the ducts are known as ductal carcinomas, while those developing from lobules are known as lobular carcinomas.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] There are more than 18 other sub-types of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The diagnosis of breast cancer is confirmed by taking a biopsy of the concerning tissue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Once the diagnosis is made, further tests are carried out to determine if the cancer has spread beyond the breast and which treatments are most likely to be effective.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancer screening can be instrumental, given that the size of a breast cancer and its spread are among the most critical factors in predicting the prognosis of the disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancers found during screening are typically smaller and less likely to have spread outside the breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Training health workers to do clinical breast examination may have potential to detect breast cancer at an early stage.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A 2013 Cochrane review found that it was unclear whether mammographic screening does more harm than good, in that a large proportion of women who test positive turn out not to have the disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A 2009 review for the US Preventive Services Task Force found evidence of benefit in those 40 to 70 years of age, and the organization recommends screening every two years in women ages 50 to 74.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The medications tamoxifen or raloxifene may be used in an effort to prevent breast cancer in those who are at high risk of developing it.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Surgical removal of both breasts is another preventive measure in some high risk women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In those who have been diagnosed with cancer, several treatments may be used, including surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, hormonal therapy, and targeted therapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Types of surgery vary from breast-conserving surgery to mastectomy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast reconstruction may take place at the time of surgery or at a later date.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In those in whom the cancer has spread to other parts of the body, treatments are mostly aimed at improving quality of life and comfort.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Outcomes for breast cancer vary depending on the cancer type, the extent of disease, and the person's age.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The five-year survival rates in United States and in the UK are over 90%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In developing countries, five-year survival rates are lower.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Worldwide, breast cancer is the leading type of cancer in women, accounting for 25% of all cases.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In 2018, it resulted in two million new cases and 627,000 deaths.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] It is more common in developed countries, and is more than 100 times more common in women than in men.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] For transgender individuals on gender-affirming hormone therapy, breast cancer is five times more common in cisgender women than in transgender men, and 46 times more common in transgender women than in cisgender men.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Most people with breast cancer have no symptoms at the time of diagnosis; a breast cancer screening test detects their tumor.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] For those who do have symptoms, a new lump in the breast is most common.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Most breast lumps are not cancerous, though lumps that are painless, hard, and with irregular edges are more likely to be cancerous.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Other symptoms include skin thickening known as peau d'orange swelling or pain in the breast; dimpling, thickening, redness, or dryness of the breast skin; and pain, or inversion of the nipple.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Some may experience unusual discharge from the breasts, or swelling of the lymph nodes under the arms or along the collar bone.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Some less common forms of breast cancer cause distinctive symptoms.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Up to 5% of people with breast cancer have inflammatory breast cancer, where cancer cells block the lymph vessels of one breast, causing the breast to swell substantially and redden over three to six months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Up to 3% of people with breast cancer have Paget's disease of the breast, with eczema-like red, scaly irritation on the nipple and areola.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Advanced tumors can spread (metastasize) beyond the breast, most commonly to the bones, liver, lungs, and brain.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Bone metastases can cause swelling, progressive bone pain, and weakening of the bones that leads to fractures.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Liver metastases can cause abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and skin problems – rash, itchy skin, or yellowing of the skin (jaundice).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with lung metastases experience chest pain, shortness of breath, and regular coughing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Metastases in the brain can cause persistent headache, seizures, nausea, vomiting, and disruptions to the affected person's speech, vision, memory, and regular behavior.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancer screening refers to testing women without breast cancer symptoms in an attempt to diagnose breast tumors early, when treatments are more successful.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The most common screening test for breast cancer is low-dose X-ray imaging of the breast, called mammography.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Each breast is pressed between two plates and imaged.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Tumors can appear unusually dense within the breast, distort the shape of surrounding tissue, or cause small dense flecks called microcalcifications.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Radiologists generally report mammogram results on a standardized scale – the six-point Breast Imaging-Reporting and Data System (BI-RADS) is the most common globally – where a higher number corresponds to a greater risk of a cancerous tumor.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A mammogram also reveals breast density; dense breast tissue appears opaque on a mammogram and can obscure tumors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] BI-RADS categorizes breast density into four categories.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Mammography can detect around 90% of breast tumors in the least dense breasts (called "fatty" breasts), but just 60% in the most dense breasts (called "extremely dense").
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women with particularly dense breasts can instead be screened by ultrasound, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), or tomosynthesis, all of which more sensitively detect breast tumors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Regular screening mammography reduces breast cancer deaths by at least 20%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Most medical guidelines recommend annual screening mammograms for women aged 50–70.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Screening also reduces breast cancer mortality in women aged 40–49, and some guidelines recommend annual screening in this age group as well.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] For women at high risk for developing breast cancer, most guidelines recommend adding MRI screening to mammography to increase the chance of detecting potentially dangerous tumors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Regularly feeling one's own breasts for lumps or other abnormalities, called breast self-examination, does not reduce a person's chance of dying from breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Clinical breast exams, where a health professional feels the breasts for abnormalities, are common; whether they reduce the risk of dying from breast cancer is not known.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Regular breast cancer screening is commonplace in most wealthy nations, but remains uncommon in the world's poorer countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those who have a suspected tumor from a mammogram or physical exam first undergo additional imaging – typically a second "diagnostic" mammogram and ultrasound – to confirm its presence and location.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A biopsy is then taken of the suspected tumor.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast biopsy is typically done by core needle biopsy, with a hollow needle used to collect tissue from the area of interest.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Suspected tumors that appear to be filled with fluid are often instead sampled by fine-needle aspiration.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Around 10–20% of breast biopsies are positive for cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Most biopsied breast masses are instead caused by fibrocystic breast changes, a term that encompasses benign pockets of fluid, cell growth, or fibrous tissue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancers are classified by several grading systems, each of which assesses a tumor characteristic that impacts a person's prognosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] First, a tumor is classified by the tissue it arises from, or the appearance of the tumor tissue under a microscope.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Most breast cancers (85%) are ductal carcinoma – derived from the lining of the mammary ducts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] 10% are lobular carcinoma – derived from the mammary lobes – or mixed ductal/lobular carcinoma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Rarer types include mucinous carcinoma (around 2.5% of cases; surrounded by mucin), tubular carcinoma (1.5%; full of small tubes of epithelial cells), medullary carcinoma (1%; resembling "medullary" or middle-layer tissue), and papillary carcinoma (1%; covered in finger-like growths).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Oftentimes, a biopsy reveals cells that are cancerous but have not yet spread beyond their original location.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] This condition, called carcinoma in situ, is often considered "precancerous" rather than a dangerous cancer itself.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with ductal carcinoma in situ (in the mammary ducts) are at increased risk for developing true invasive breast cancer – around a third develop breast cancer within five years.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Lobular carcinoma in situ (in the mammary lobes) rarely causes a noticeable lump, and is often found incidentally during a biopsy for another reason.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] It is commonly spread throughout both breasts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with lobular carcinoma in situ also have an increased risk of developing breast cancer – around 1% develop breast cancer each year.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] However, their risk of dying of breast cancer is no higher than that of the rest of the population.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Invasive tumor tissue is assigned a grade based on how distinct it appears from healthy breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast tumors are graded on three features: the proportion of cancer cells that form tubules, the appearance of the cell nucleus, and how many cells are actively replicating.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Each feature is scored on a three-point scale, with a higher score indicating less healthy-looking tissue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A grade is assigned based on the sum of the three scores.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Combined scores of 3, 4, or 5 represent grade 1, a slower-growing cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Scores of 8 or 9 represent grade 3, a faster-growing, more aggressive cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In addition to grading, tumor biopsy samples are tested by immunohistochemistry to determine if the tissue contains the proteins estrogen receptor (ER), progesterone receptor (PR), or human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Tumors containing either ER or PR are called "hormone receptor-positive" and can be treated with hormone therapies.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Around 15 to 20% of tumors contain HER2; these can be treated with HER2-targeted therapies.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The remainder that do not contain ER, PR, or HER2 are called "triple-negative" tumors, and tend to grow more quickly than other breast cancer types.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] After the tumor is evaluated, the breast cancer case is staged using the American Joint Committee on Cancer and Union for International Cancer Control's TNM staging system.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Scores are assigned based on characteristics of the tumor (T), lymph nodes (N), and any metastases (M).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] T scores are determined by the size and extent of the tumor.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Tumors less than 2 centimeters (cm) across are designated T1.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Tumors that extend to the chest wall or to the skin are designated T4.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] N scores are based on whether the cancer has spread to nearby lymph nodes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] N0 indicates no spread to the lymph nodes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] N1 is for tumors that have spread to the closest axillary lymph nodes (called "level I" and "level II" axillary lymph nodes, in the armpit).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] N2 is for spread to the intramammary lymph nodes (on the other side of the breast, near the chest center), or for axillary lymph nodes that appear attached to each other or to the tissue around them (a sign of more severely affected tissue).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] N3 designates tumors that have spread to the highest axillary lymph nodes (called "level 3" axillary lymph nodes, above the armpit near the shoulder), to the supraclavicular lymph nodes (along the neck), or to both the axillary and intramammary lymph nodes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The M score is binary: M0 indicates no evidence metastases; M1 indicates metastases have been detected.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] TNM scores are then combined with tumor grades and ER/PR/HER2 status to calculate a cancer case's "prognostic stage group".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Stage groups range from I (best prognosis) to IV (worst prognosis), with groups I, II, and III further divided into subgroups IA, IB, IIA, IIB, IIIA, IIIB, and IIIC.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In general, tumors of higher T and N scores and higher grades are assigned higher stage groups.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Tumors that are ER, PR, and HER2 positive are slightly lower stage group than those that are negative.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Tumors that have metastasized are stage IV, regardless of the other scored characteristics.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The management of breast cancer depends on the affected person's health, the cancer case's molecular characteristics, and how far the tumor has spread at the time of diagnosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those whose tumors have not spread beyond the breast often undergo surgery to remove the tumor and some surrounding breast tissue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The surgery method is typically chosen to spare as much healthy breast tissue as possible, removing just the tumor (lumpectomy) or a larger part of the breast (partial mastectomy).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with large or multiple tumors, high genetic risk of subsequent cancers, or who are unable to receive radiation therapy may instead opt for full removal of the affected breast(s) (full mastectomy).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] To reduce the risk of cancer spreading, women will often have the nearest lymph node removed in a procedure called sentinel lymph node biopsy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Dye is injected near the tumor site, and several hours later, the lymph node in which the dye accumulates is removed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] After surgery, many undergo radiotherapy to decrease the chance of cancer recurrence.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those who had lumpectomies receive radiation to the whole breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those who had a mastectomy and are at elevated risk of tumor spread – tumor greater than five centimeters wide, or cancerous cells in nearby lymph nodes – receive radiation to the mastectomy scar and chest wall.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] If cancerous cells have spread to nearby lymph nodes, those lymph nodes will be irradiated as well.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Radiation is typically given five days per week, for up to seven weeks.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Radiotherapy for breast cancer is typically delivered via external beam radiotherapy, where a device focuses radiation beams onto the targeted parts of the body.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Instead, some undergo brachytherapy, where radioactive material is placed into a device inserted at the surgical site from which the tumor was removed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Fresh radioactive material is added twice a day for five days, then the device is removed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Surgery plus radiation typically eliminates a person's breast tumor.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Less than 5% of those treated have their breast tumor grow back.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] After surgery and radiation, the breast can be surgically reconstructed, either by adding a breast implant or transferring excess tissue from another part of the body.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Chemotherapy reduces the chance of cancer recurring in the next ten years by around a third.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] However, 1-2% of those on chemotherapy experience life-threatening or permanent side effects.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] To balance these benefits and risks, chemotherapy is typically offered to those with a higher risk of cancer recurrence.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] There is no established risk cutoff for offering chemotherapy; determining who should receive chemotherapy is controversial.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Chemotherapy drugs are typically given in two- to three-week cycles, with periods of drug treatment interspersed with rest periods to recover from the therapies' side effects.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Chemotherapies from different classes are typically given in combination, with particular chemotherapy drugs selected based on the affected person's health and the different chemotherapeutics' side effects.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Anthrocyclines and cyclophosphamide cause leukemia in up to 1% of those treated.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Anthrocyclines also cause congestive heart failure in around 1% of people treated.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Taxanes cause peripheral neuropathy, which is permanent in up to 5% of those treated.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The same chemotherapy agents can be given before surgery – called neoadjuvant therapy – to shrink tumors, making them easier to remove safely.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] For those whose tumors are HER2-positive, adding the HER2-targeted antibody trastuzumab to chemotherapy reduces the chance of cancer recurrence and death by at least a third.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Trastuzumab is given weekly or every three weeks for twelve months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Adding a second HER2-targeted antibody, pertuzumab slightly enhances treatment efficacy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In rare cases, trastuzumab can disrupt heart function, and so it is typically not given in conjunction with anthracyclines, which can also damage the heart.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] After their chemotherapy course, those whose tumors are ER-positive or PR-positive benefit from endocrine therapy, which reduces the levels of estrogens and progesterones that hormone receptor-positive breast cancers require to survive.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Tamoxifen treatment blocks the ER in the breast and some other tissues, and reduces the risk of breast cancer death by around 40% over the next ten years.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Chemically blocking estrogen production with GnRH-targeted drugs (goserelin, leuprolide, or triptorelin) and aromatase inhibitors (anastrozole, letrozole, or exemestane) slightly improves survival, but has more severe side effects.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Side effects of estrogen depletion include hot flashes, vaginal discomfort, and muscle and joint pain.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Endocrine therapy is typically recommended for at least five years after surgery and chemotherapy, and is sometimes continued for 10 years or longer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women with breast cancer who had a lumpectomy or a mastectomy and kept their other breast have similar survival rates to those who had a double mastectomy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] There seems to be no survival advantage to removing the other breast, with only a 7% chance of cancer occurring in the other breast over 20 years.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] For around 1 in 5 people treated for localized breast cancer, their tumors eventually spread to distant body sites – most commonly the nearby bones (67% of cases), liver (41%), lungs (37%), brain (13%), and peritoneum (10%).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with metastatic disease can receive further chemotherapy, typically starting with capecitabine, an anthracycline, or a taxane.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] As one chemotherapy drug fails to control the cancer, another is started.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In addition to the chemotherapeutic drugs used for localized cancer, gemcitabine, vinorelbine, etoposide, and epothilones are sometimes effective.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with bone metastases benefit from regular infusion of the bone-strengthening agents denosumab and the bisphosphonates; infusion every three months reduces the chance of bone pain, fractures, and bone hypercalcemia.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Up to 70% of those with ER-positive metastatic breast cancer benefit from additional endocrine therapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Therapy options include those used in localized cancer, plus toremifene and fulvestrant, often used in combination with CDK4/6 inhibitors (palbociclib, ribociclib, or abemaciclib).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] When one endocrine therapy fails, most will benefit from transitioning to a second one.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Some respond to a third sequential therapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Adding an mTOR inhibitor, everolimus, can further slow the tumors' progression.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with HER2-positive metastatic disease can benefit from continued use of trastuzumab, alone, in combination with pertuzumab, or in combination with chemotherapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those whose tumors continue to progress on trastuzumab benefit from HER2-targeted antibody drug conjugates (HER2 antibodies linked to chemotherapy drugs) trastuzumab emtansine or trastuzumab deruxtecan.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The HER2-targeted antibody margetuximab can also prolong survival, as can HER2 inhibitors lapatinib, neratinib, or tucatinib.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Certain therapies are targeted at those whose tumors have specific gene mutations: Alpelisib or capivasertib for those with mutations activating the protein PIK3CA.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] PARP inhibitors (olaparib and talazoparib) for those with mutations that inactivate BRCA1 or BRCA2.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The immune checkpoint inhibitor antibody atezolizumab for those whose tumors express PD-L1.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] And the similar immunotherapy pembrolizumab for those whose tumors have mutations in various DNA repair pathways.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Imlunestrant (Inluriyo) was approved for medical use in the United States in September 2025.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Many breast cancer therapies have side effects that can be alleviated with appropriate supportive care.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Chemotherapy causes hair loss, nausea, and vomiting in nearly everyone who receives it.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Antiemetic drugs can alleviate nausea and vomiting; cooling the scalp with a cold cap during chemotherapy treatments may reduce hair loss.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Many complain of cognitive issues during chemotherapy treatment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] These usually resolve within a few months of the end of chemotherapy treatment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those on endocrine therapy often experience hot flashes, muscle and joint pain, and vaginal dryness/discomfort that can lead to issues having sex.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Around half of women have their hot flashes alleviated by taking antidepressants; pain can be treated with physical therapy and nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs; counseling and use of personal lubricants can improve sexual issues.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In women with non-metastatic breast cancer, psychological interventions such as cognitive behavioral therapy can have positive effects on outcomes such as cognitive impairment, anxiety, depression and mood disturbance, and can also improve the quality of life.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Physical activity interventions, yoga and meditation may also have beneficial effects on health related quality of life, cognitive impairment, anxiety, fitness and physical activity in women with breast cancer following adjuvant therapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In-person and virtual peer support groups for patients and survivors of breast cancer can promote quality of life and companionship based on similar lived experiences.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The potential benefits of peer support are particularly impactful for women with breast cancer facing additional unique challenges related to ethnicity and socioeconomic status.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Peer support groups tailored to adolescents and young adult women can improve coping strategies against age-specific types of distress associated with breast cancer, including post-traumatic stress disorder and body image issues.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Different countries have different prognoses.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In the United States, the UK, South Korea, Japan, and Australia, more than 90% of women survive breast cancer for at least five years from diagnosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancer prognosis varies widely depending on how far the tumor has spread at the time of diagnosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Overall, 92% of women diagnosed with breast cancer in the United States survive at least five years from diagnosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those whose tumor(s) are completely confined to the breast (nearly two-thirds of cases) have the best prognoses – 100% survive at least five years.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those whose tumors have metastasized to distant sites have relatively poor prognoses – 33% survive at least five years from the time of diagnosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Triple-negative breast cancer (up to 15% of cases) and inflammatory breast cancer (up to 5% of cases) are particularly aggressive and have relatively poor prognoses.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with triple-negative breast cancer have an overall five-year survival rate of 78% – 92% for those whose tumors are confined to the breast; 15% for those with metastases.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those with inflammatory breast cancer are diagnosed after the cancer has already spread to the skin of the breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] They have an overall five-year survival rate of 40%; 22% for those with metastases.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The relatively rare tumors with tubular, mucinous, or medullary growth tend to have better prognoses.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In addition to the factors that influence cancer staging, a person's age can also impact prognosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancer before age 35 is rare and is more likely to be associated with a genetic predisposition to aggressive cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Conversely, breast cancer in those aged over 75 is associated with poorer prognosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Up to 80% of the variation in breast cancer frequency across countries is due to differences in reproductive history that impact a woman's levels of female sex hormones (estrogens).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women who begin menstruating earlier (before age 12) or who undergo menopause later (after 51) are at increased risk of developing breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women who give birth early in life are protected from breast cancer – someone who gives birth as a teenager has around a 70% lower risk of developing breast cancer than someone who does not have children.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] That protection wanes with higher maternal age at first birth, and disappears completely by age 35.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breastfeeding also reduces one's chance of developing breast cancer, with an approximately 4% reduction in breast cancer risk for every 12 months of breastfeeding experience.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Those who lack functioning ovaries have reduced levels of estrogens, and therefore greatly reduced breast cancer risk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Hormone replacement therapy for treatment of menopause symptoms can also increase a woman's risk of developing breast cancer, though the effect depends on the type and duration of therapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Combined progesterone/estrogen therapy increases breast cancer risk – approximately doubling one's risk after 6–7 years of treatment (though the same therapy decreases the risk of colorectal cancer).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Hormone treatment with estrogen alone has no effect on breast cancer risk, but increases one's risk of developing endometrial cancer, and therefore is only given to women who have undergone hysterectomies.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In the 1980s, the abortion–breast cancer hypothesis posited that induced abortion increased the risk of developing breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] This hypothesis was the subject of extensive scientific inquiry, which concluded that neither miscarriages nor abortions are associated with a heightened risk for breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The use of hormonal birth control does not cause breast cancer for most women; if it has an effect, it is small (on the order of 0.01% per user–year), temporary, and offset by the users' significantly reduced risk of ovarian and endometrial cancers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Among those with a family history of breast cancer, use of modern oral contraceptives does not appear to affect the risk of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Drinking alcoholic beverages increases the risk of breast cancer, even among very light drinkers (women drinking less than half of one alcoholic drink per day).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The risk is highest among heavy drinkers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Globally, about one in ten cases of breast cancer is caused by women drinking alcoholic beverages.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Alcohol use is among the most common modifiable risk factors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Obesity and diabetes increase the risk of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A high body mass index (BMI) causes 7% of breast cancers; diabetes mellitus is responsible for 2%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] At the same time, the correlation between obesity and breast cancer is not at all linear.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Studies show that those who rapidly gain weight in adulthood are at higher risk than those who have been overweight since childhood.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Likewise, excess fat in the midriff seems to induce a higher risk than excess weight carried in the lower body.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Dietary factors that may increase risk include a high-fat diet and obesity-related high cholesterol levels.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Dietary iodine deficiency may also play a role in the development of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Smoking tobacco appears to increase the risk of breast cancer, with the greater the amount smoked and the earlier in life that smoking began, the higher the risk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In those who are long-term smokers, the relative risk is increased by 35% to 50%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A lack of physical activity has been linked to about 10% of cases.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Sitting regularly for prolonged periods is associated with higher mortality from breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Regular exercise does not eliminate the risk, though it reduces it.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Actions to prevent breast cancer include not drinking alcoholic beverages, maintaining a healthy body composition, avoiding smoking, and eating healthy food.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Combining all of these (leading the healthiest possible lifestyle) would make almost a quarter of breast cancer cases worldwide preventable.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The remaining three-quarters of breast cancer cases cannot be prevented through lifestyle changes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Environmental exposure to higher levels of air pollution, specifically NO2, has been related to increased incidence of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Effects may be greater for certain types of breast cancer (ER+/PR+ > ER−/PR−) and menopausal stage (premenopausal > postmenopausal).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Some results also support a connection between historical exposure to PM2.5 and increased incidence.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A number of chemicals have been linked to breast cancer progression.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Some may affect estrogen and the endocrine system, while others promote metastasis to secondary sites and resistance to chemotherapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Environmental chemical disruptors include polychlorinated biphenyls, organochlorine pesticides, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, and phthalates.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Although the radiation from mammography is a low dose, it is estimated that yearly screening from 40 to 80 years of age will cause approximately 225 cases of fatal breast cancer per million women screened.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Other risk factors include circadian disruptions related to shift-work and routine late-night eating.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Around 10% of those with breast cancer have a family history of the disease or genetic factors that put them at higher risk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women who have had a first-degree relative (mother or sister) diagnosed with breast cancer are at a 30–50% increased risk of being diagnosed with breast cancer themselves.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In those with zero, one, or two affected relatives, the risk of breast cancer before the age of 80 is 7.8%, 13.3%, and 21.1%, with a subsequent mortality from the disease of 2.3%, 4.2%, and 7.6%, respectively.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women with certain genetic variants are at higher risk of developing breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The most well known are variants of the BRCA genes *BRCA1* and *BRCA2*.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women with pathogenic variants in either gene have around a 70% chance of developing breast cancer in their lifetime, as well as an approximately 33% chance of developing ovarian cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Pathogenic variants in *PALB2* – a gene whose product directly interacts with that of *BRCA2* – also increase breast cancer risk; a woman with such a variant has around a 50% increased risk of developing breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Variants in other tumor suppressor genes can also increase one's risk of developing breast cancer, namely *p53* (causes Li–Fraumeni syndrome), *PTEN* (causes Cowden syndrome), and *PALB1*.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast changes like atypical ductal hyperplasia found in benign breast conditions such as fibrocystic breast changes, are correlated with an increased breast cancer risk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Diabetes might also increase the risk of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Autoimmune diseases such as lupus erythematosus seem also to increase the risk for the acquisition of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women whose breasts have been exposed to substantial radiation doses before the age of 30 – typically due to repeated chest fluoroscopies or treatment for Hodgkin lymphoma – are at increased risk for developing breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Radioactive iodine therapy (used to treat thyroid disease) and radiation exposures after age 30 are not associated with breast cancer risk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Based on the existence or lack of molecular markers for the estrogen receptor (ER), progesterone receptor (PR), and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (ERBB2; formerly HER2), breast cancer is divided into three main categories.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] About 70% of patients have hormone receptor-positive/ERBB2-negative tumours, which are the most prevalent type.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] About 15% of cases are triple-negative (lacking all three conventional markers), whereas 15%–20% of cases are ERBB2-positive.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] While hormone receptor-positive tumours are more common in elderly women, triple-negative breast cancer is more common in younger Black or Hispanic women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The major causes of sporadic breast cancer are associated with hormone levels.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] This hormone activates the development of the breasts throughout puberty, menstrual cycles, and pregnancy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The imbalance between estrogen and progesterone during the menstrual phases causes cell proliferation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Moreover, oxidative metabolites of estrogen can increase DNA damage and mutations.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Repeated cycling and the impairment of the repair process can transform a normal cell into a pre-malignant and eventually malignant cell through mutation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] During the pre-malignant stage, high proliferation of stromal cells can be activated by estrogen to support the development of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] During ligand-binding activation, the ER can regulate gene expression by interacting with estrogen response elements within the promoter of specific genes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The expression and activation of ER due to a lack of estrogen can be stimulated by extracellular signals.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The ER directly binding with the several proteins, including growth factor receptors, can promote the expression of genes related to cell growth and survival.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancer, like other cancers, occurs because of an interaction between an environmental (external) factor and a genetically susceptible host.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Normal cells divide as many times as needed and stop.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] They attach to other cells and stay in place in tissues.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Cells become cancerous when they lose their ability to stop dividing, to attach to other cells, to stay where they belong, and to die at the proper time.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Normal cells will self-destruct (programmed cell death) when they are no longer needed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Until then, cells are protected from programmed death by several protein clusters and pathways.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] One of the protective pathways is the PI3K/AKT pathway; another is the RAS/MEK/ERK pathway.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Sometimes the genes along these protective pathways are mutated in a way that turns them permanently "on", rendering the cell incapable of self-destructing when it is no longer needed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] This is one of the steps that causes cancer in combination with other mutations.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Normally, the *PTEN* protein turns off the PI3K/AKT pathway when the cell is ready for programmed cell death.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In some breast cancers, the gene for the *PTEN* protein is mutated, so the PI3K/AKT pathway is stuck in the "on" position, and the cancer cell does not self-destruct.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Mutations that can lead to breast cancer have been experimentally linked to estrogen exposure.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Additionally, G-protein coupled estrogen receptors have been associated with various cancers of the female reproductive system, including breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Abnormal growth factor signaling in the interaction between stromal cells and epithelial cells can facilitate malignant cell growth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In breast adipose tissue, overexpression of leptin leads to increased cell proliferation and cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Some mutations associated with cancer, such as p53, *BRCA1* and *BRCA2*, occur in mechanisms to correct errors in DNA.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The inherited mutation in *BRCA1* or *BRCA2* genes can interfere with the repair of DNA crosslinks and double-strand breaks (known functions of the encoded protein).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] These carcinogens cause DNA damage such as DNA crosslinks and double-strand breaks that often require repairs by pathways containing *BRCA1* and *BRCA2*.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] GATA-3 directly controls the expression of estrogen receptor (ER) and other genes associated with epithelial differentiation, and the loss of GATA-3 leads to loss of differentiation and poor prognosis due to cancer cell invasion and metastasis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women can reduce their risk of breast cancer by maintaining a healthy weight, reducing alcohol use, increasing physical activity, and breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] These modifications might prevent 38% of breast cancers in the US, 42% in the UK, 28% in Brazil, and 20% in China.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The benefits with moderate exercise such as brisk walking are seen at all age groups including postmenopausal women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] High levels of physical activity reduce the risk of breast cancer by about 14%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Strategies that encourage regular physical activity and reduce obesity could also have other benefits, such as reduced risks of cardiovascular disease and diabetes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] A study that included data from 130,957 women of European ancestry found "strong evidence that greater levels of physical activity and less sedentary time are likely to reduce breast cancer risk, with results generally consistent across breast cancer subtypes".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The American Cancer Society and the American Society of Clinical Oncology advised in 2016 that people should eat a diet high in vegetables, fruits, whole grains, and legumes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Eating foods rich in soluble fiber contributes to reducing breast cancer risk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] High intake of citrus fruit has been associated with a 10% reduction in the risk of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Marine omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids appear to reduce the risk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] High consumption of soy-based foods may reduce risk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Removal of the breasts before breast cancer develops (called preventive mastectomy) reduces the risk of developing breast cancer by more than 95%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In women genetically predisposed to developing breast cancer, preventive mastectomy reduces their risk of dying from breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] For those at normal risk, preventive mastectomy does not reduce their chance of dying, and so is generally not recommended.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Removing the second breast in a person who has breast cancer (contralateral risk-reducing mastectomy or CRRM) may reduce the risk of cancer in the second breast, but it is not clear whether removing the second breast improves the chance of survival.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] An increasing number of women who test positive for faulty *BRCA1* or *BRCA2* genes choose to have risk-reducing surgery.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The average wait time to undergo the procedure is 2 years, which is much longer than recommended.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Selective estrogen receptor modulators (SERMs) reduce the risk of breast cancer but increase the risk of thromboembolism and endometrial cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] There is no overall change in the risk of death.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] They are thus not recommended for the prevention of breast cancer in women at average risk but it is recommended they be offered for those at high risk and over the age of 35.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The benefit of breast cancer reduction continues for at least five years after stopping a course of treatment with these medications.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Aromatase inhibitors (such as exemestane and anastrozole) may be more effective than SERMs (such as tamoxifen) at reducing breast cancer risk and they are not associated with an increased risk of endometrial cancer and thromboembolism.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancer is the most common invasive cancer in women in most countries, accounting for 30% of cancer cases in women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] In 2022, an estimated 2.3 million women were diagnosed with breast cancer, and 670,000 died of the disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The incidence of breast cancer is rising by around 3% per year, as populations in many countries are getting older.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Rates of breast cancer vary across the world, but generally correlate with wealth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Around 1 in 12 women are diagnosed with breast cancer in wealthier countries, compared to 1 in 27 in lower-income countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Most of that difference is due to differences in menstrual and reproductive histories – women in wealthier countries tend to begin menstruating earlier and have children later, both factors that increase risk of developing breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] People in lower-income countries tend to have less access to breast cancer screening and treatments, and so breast cancer death rates tend to be higher.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] 1 in 71 women die of breast cancer in wealthy countries, while 1 in 48 die of the disease in lower-income countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Breast cancer predominantly affects women; less than 1% of those with breast cancer are men.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] Women can develop breast cancer as early as adolescence.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The risk increases with age, and 75% of cases are in women over 50 years old.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p01] The risk over a woman's lifetime is approximately 1.5% at age 40, 3% at age 50, and more than 4% risk at age 70.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Because of its visibility, breast cancer was the form of cancer most often described in ancient documents.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Because autopsies were rare, cancers of the internal organs were essentially invisible to ancient medicine.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Breast cancer, however, could be felt through the skin, and in its advanced state often developed into fungating lesions: the tumor would become necrotic (die from the inside, causing the tumor to appear to break up) and ulcerate through the skin, weeping fetid, dark fluid.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The oldest discovered evidence of breast cancer is from Egypt; it dates back 4200 years, to the Sixth Dynasty.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The study of a woman's remains from the necropolis of Qubbet el-Hawa showed the typical destructive damage due to metastatic spread.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The Edwin Smith Papyrus describes eight cases of tumors or ulcers of the breast that were treated by cauterization.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The writing says about the disease, "There is no treatment." For centuries, physicians described similar cases in their practices, with the same conclusion.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Ancient medicine, from the time of the Greeks through the 17th century, was based on humoralism, and thus believed that breast cancer was generally caused by imbalances in the fundamental fluids that controlled the body, especially an excess of black bile.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Alternatively it was seen as divine punishment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Mastectomy for breast cancer was performed at least as early as AD 548, when it was proposed by the court physician Aetios of Amida to Theodora.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] It was not until doctors achieved greater understanding of the circulatory system in the 17th century that they could link breast cancer's spread to the lymph nodes in the armpit.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In the early 18th century, the French surgeon Jean Louis Petit performed total mastectomies that included removing the axillary lymph nodes, as he recognized that this reduced recurrence.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Petit's work built on the methods of the surgeon Bernard Peyrilhe, who in the 17th century additionally removed the pectoral muscle underlying the breast, as he judged that this greatly improved the prognosis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Physicians were conservative in the treatment they prescribed in the early stages of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Patients were treated with a mixture of detox purges, blood letting, and traditional remedies that were supposed to lower acidity, such as the alkaline arsenic.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] When in 1664 Anne of Austria was diagnosed with breast cancer, the initial treatment involved compresses saturated with hemlock juice.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] When the lumps increased, the King's physician commenced a treatment with arsenic ointments.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The royal patient died in 1666 in atrocious pain.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Each failing treatment for breast cancer led to the search for new treatments, spurring a market in remedies that were advertised and sold by quacks, herbalists, chemists and apothecaries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The lack of anesthesia and antiseptics made mastectomy a painful and dangerous ordeal.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In the 18th century, a wide variety of anatomical discoveries were accompanied by new theories about the cause and growth of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The investigative surgeon John Hunter claimed that neural fluid generated breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Other surgeons proposed that milk within the mammary ducts led to cancerous growths.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Theories about trauma to the breast as a cause for malignant changes in breast tissue were advanced.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The discovery of breast lumps and swellings fueled controversies about hard tumors and whether lumps were benign stages of cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Medical opinion about the necessary immediate treatment varied.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The surgeon Benjamin Bell advocated removal of the entire breast, even when only a portion was affected.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Breast cancer was uncommon until the 19th century, when improvements in sanitation and control of deadly infectious diseases resulted in dramatic increases in lifespan.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Previously, most women had died too young to have developed breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In 1878, an article in *Scientific American* described historical treatment by pressure intended to induce local ischemia in cases when surgical removal were not possible.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] William Stewart Halsted started performing radical mastectomies in 1882, helped greatly by advances in general surgical technology, such as aseptic technique and anesthesia.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The Halsted radical mastectomy often involved removing both breasts, associated lymph nodes, and the underlying chest muscles.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] This often led to long-term pain and disability, but was seen as necessary to prevent the cancer from recurring.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Before the advent of the Halsted radical mastectomy, 20-year survival rates were only 10%; Halsted's surgery raised that rate to 50%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Breast cancer staging systems were developed in the 1920s and 1930s to determining the extent to which a cancer has developed by growing and spreading.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The first case-controlled study on breast cancer epidemiology was done by Janet Lane-Claypon, who published a comparative study in 1926 of 500 breast cancer cases and 500 controls of the same background and lifestyle for the British Ministry of Health.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Radical mastectomies remained the standard of care in the USA until the 1970s, but in Europe, breast-sparing procedures, often followed by radiation therapy, were generally adopted in the 1950s.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In 1955, George Crile Jr. published *Cancer and Common Sense* arguing that cancer patients needed to understand available treatment options.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Crile became a close friend of the environmentalist Rachel Carson, who had undergone a Halsted radical mastectomy in 1960 to treat her malignant breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The US oncologist Jerome Urban promoted super radical mastectomies, taking even more tissue, until 1963, when the ten-year survival rates proved equal to the less-damaging radical mastectomy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Carson died in 1964, and Crile went on to publish a wide variety of articles, both in the popular press and in medical journals, challenging the widespread use of the Halsted radical mastectomy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In 1973, Crile published *What Women Should Know About the Breast Cancer Controversy*.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In 1974, Betty Ford was diagnosed with breast cancer, and the options for treating breast cancer were openly discussed in the press.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] During the 1970s, a new understanding of metastasis led to perceiving cancer as a systemic illness as well as a localized one, and more sparing procedures were developed that proved equally effective.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In the 1980s and 1990s, thousands of women who had successfully completed standard treatment then demanded and received high-dose bone marrow transplants, thinking this would lead to better long-term survival.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] However, it proved completely ineffective, and 15–20% of women died because of the brutal treatment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The 1995 reports from the Nurses' Health Study and the 2002 conclusions of the Women's Health Initiative trial conclusively proved that HRT significantly increased the incidence of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Before the 20th century, breast cancer was feared and discussed in hushed tones, as if it were shameful.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] As little could be safely done with primitive surgical techniques, women tended to suffer silently rather than seek care.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] When surgery advanced, and long-term survival rates improved, women began raising awareness of the disease and the possibility of successful treatment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The "Women's Field Army", run by the American Society for the Control of Cancer (later the American Cancer Society) during the 1930s and 1940s, was one of the first organized campaigns.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In 1952, the first peer-to-peer support group, called "Reach to Recovery", began providing post-mastectomy, in-hospital visits from women who had survived breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The breast cancer movement of the 1980s and 1990s developed out of the larger feminist movements and women's health movement of the 20th century.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] This series of political and educational campaigns, partly inspired by the politically and socially effective AIDS awareness campaigns, resulted in the widespread acceptance of second opinions before surgery, less invasive surgical procedures, support groups, and other advances in care.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] A pink ribbon is the most prominent symbol of breast cancer awareness.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Pink ribbons, which can be made inexpensively, are sometimes sold as fundraisers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] They may be worn to honor those who have been diagnosed with breast cancer, or to identify products that the manufacturer would like to sell to consumers who are interested in breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In the 1990s, breast cancer awareness campaigns were launched by US-based corporations.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] As part of these cause-related marketing campaigns, corporations donated to a variety of breast cancer initiatives for every pink ribbon product that was purchased.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The *Wall Street Journal* noted that "the strong emotions provoked by breast cancer translate to a company's bottom line".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] While many US corporations donated to existing breast cancer initiatives, others, such as Avon, established their own breast cancer foundations on the back of pink ribbon products.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Wearing or displaying a pink ribbon has been criticized by the opponents of this practice as a kind of slacktivism, because it has no practical positive effect.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] It has also been criticized as hypocrisy, because some people wear the pink ribbon to show goodwill towards women with breast cancer, but then oppose these women's practical goals, like patient rights and anti-pollution legislation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Critics say that the feel-good nature of pink ribbons and pink consumption distracts society from the lack of progress on preventing and curing breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] It is also criticized for reinforcing gender stereotypes and objectifying women and their breasts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Breast Cancer Action launched the "Think Before You Pink" campaign in 2002 against pinkwashing, to target businesses that have co-opted the pink campaign to promote products that cause breast cancer, such as alcoholic beverages.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In her 2006 book *Pink Ribbons, Inc.: Breast Cancer and the Politics of Philanthropy* Samantha King claimed that breast cancer has been transformed from a serious disease and individual tragedy to a market-driven industry of survivorship and corporate sales pitch.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In the same year Barbara Ehrenreich published an opinion piece in *Harper's Magazine*, lamenting that in breast cancer culture, breast cancer therapy is viewed as a rite of passage rather than a disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] To fit into this mold, the woman with breast cancer needs to normalize and feminize her appearance and minimize the disruption that her health issues cause to anyone else.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Anger, sadness, and negativity must be silenced.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] As with most cultural models, people who conform to the model are given social status, in this case as cancer survivors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Women who reject the model are shunned, punished, and shamed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The culture is criticized for treating adult women like little girls, as evidenced by "baby" toys such as pink teddy bears given to adult women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] There are ethnic disparities in the mortality rates for breast cancer as well as in breast cancer treatment.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Breast cancer is the most prevalent cancer affecting women of every ethnic group in the United States.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Breast cancer incidence among Black women aged 45 and older is higher than that of white women in the same age group.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] White women aged 60–84 have higher incidence rates of breast cancer than Black women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Despite this, Black women at every age are more likely to die of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Breast cancer treatment has improved greatly over the years; however, Black women are still less likely to obtain treatment compared to white women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Risk factors such as socioeconomic status, late-stage, or breast cancer at diagnosis, genetic differences in tumor subtypes, and differences in healthcare access all contribute to these disparities.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Socioeconomic determinants affecting the disparity in breast cancer illness include poverty, culture, and social injustice.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In Hispanic women, the incidence of breast cancer is lower than in non-Hispanic women, but it is often diagnosed at a later stage than in white women with larger tumors.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Black women are usually diagnosed with breast cancer at a younger age than white women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The median age of diagnosis for Black women is 59, in comparison to 62 in White women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The incidence of breast cancer in Black women has increased by 0.4% per year since 1975, and 1.5% per year among Asian/Pacific Islander women since 1992.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Incidence rates were stable for non-Hispanic White, Hispanic, and Native American women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The five-year survival rate is noted to be 81% in Black women and 92% in White women.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Chinese and Japanese women have the highest survival rates.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Low-income, immigrant, disabled, and racial and sexual minority women are less likely to undergo breast cancer screening and thus are more likely to receive late-stage diagnoses.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Ensuring equitable health care, including breast cancer screenings, can positively affect these disparities.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Efforts to raise awareness about the significance of screenings, such as informational materials, are ineffective in reducing these disparities.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Successful methods directly address the barriers that prevent access to screenings, such as language barriers or lack of health insurance.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Through community outreach in underserved communities, patient navigators and advocates can offer women personalized assistance with attending screening and follow-up appointments.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] However, the long-term benefits are unclear, primarily due to a lack of resources and staff to sustain these community-based solutions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Legislation that requires mandatory insurance coverage of language assistance and mammograms has also increased screening rates, particularly among ethnic minority communities.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Innovative solutions proven effective include mobile screening vehicles, telehealth consultations, and online tools to assess potential risks and signs of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] A diverse pool of participants in breast cancer research facilitates the investigation of the disease's unique risks and development patterns in ethnic minority populations.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] These populations experience better health outcomes from medical treatments designed based on research with diverse patient representation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Within the United States, less than 3% of patients in clinical trials identify as Black, despite representing 12.7% of the national population.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Hispanic and indigenous women are also significantly underrepresented in breast cancer research.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Lengthy involvement in clinical trials without financial compensation discourages the participation of low-income women unable to miss work or afford traveling expenses.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Monetary compensation, language interpreters, and patient navigators can increase the diversity of participants in research and clinical trials.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Breast cancer is relatively uncommon in men, but it can occur.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Typically, a breast tumor appears as a lump in the breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Treatment typically involves surgery, followed by radiation if needed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Around 90% men's tumors are ER-positive and are treated with endocrine therapy, typically tamoxifen.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The disease course and prognosis are similar to those in women of similar age with similar disease characteristics.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Diagnosing breast cancer in pregnant women is often delayed, as symptoms can be masked by pregnancy-related breast changes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The diagnostic path is the same as in non-pregnant women, except that radiography of the abdomen is avoided.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Chemotherapy is avoided during the first trimester, but can be safely administered through the rest of the pregnancy term.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Anti-HER2 treatments and endocrine therapies are delayed until after delivery.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] These treatments given after delivery can cross into the breast milk, and so breast feeding is generally not possible.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The prognosis for pregnant women with breast cancer is similar to that of non-pregnant women of similar age.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Treatments are being evaluated in clinical trials.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] This includes individual drugs, combinations of drugs, and surgical and radiation techniques Investigations include new types of targeted therapy, cancer vaccines, oncolytic virotherapy, gene therapy and immunotherapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The latest research is reported annually at scientific meetings such as that of the American Society of Clinical Oncology, San Antonio Breast Cancer Symposium, and the St.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] These studies are reviewed by professional societies and other organizations, and formulated into guidelines for specific treatment groups and risk category.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Fenretinide, a retinoid, is also being studied as a way to reduce the risk of breast cancer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] In particular, combinations of ribociclib plus endocrine therapy have been the subject of clinical trials.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] A 2019 review found moderate certainty evidence that giving people antibiotics before breast cancer surgery helped to prevent surgical site infection (SSI).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Further study is required to determine the most effective antibiotic protocol and use in women undergoing immediate breast reconstruction.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] As of 2014, cryoablation is being studied to see if it could be a substitute for a lumpectomy in small cancers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] There is tentative evidence in those with tumors less than 2 centimeters across.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] It may also be used in those in who surgery is not possible.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Another review states that cryoablation looks promising for early breast cancer of small size.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Part of the current knowledge on breast carcinomas is based on in vivo and in vitro studies performed with cell lines derived from breast cancers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] These provide an unlimited source of homogenous self-replicating material, free of contaminating stromal cells, and often easily cultured in simple standard media.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] The first breast cancer cell line described, BT-20, was established in 1958.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Since then, and despite sustained work in this area, the number of permanent lines obtained has been strikingly low (about 100).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Indeed, attempts to culture breast cancer cell lines from primary tumors have been largely unsuccessful.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] This poor efficiency was often due to technical difficulties associated with the extraction of viable tumor cells from their surrounding stroma.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Most of the available breast cancer cell lines originated from metastatic tumors, mainly from pleural effusions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Effusions generally provided large numbers of dissociated, viable tumor cells with little or no contamination by fibroblasts and other tumor stroma cells.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] Many of the currently used BCC lines were established in the late 1970s.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breast-cancer-p02] A very few of them, namely MCF-7, T-47D, MDA-MB-231, and SK-BR-3, account for more than two-thirds of all abstracts reporting studies on the mentioned breast cancer cell lines, as concluded from a Medline-based survey.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breastfeeding has a number of benefits to both mother and baby that infant formula lacks.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Increased breastfeeding to near-universal levels in low and middle income countries could prevent approximately 820,000 deaths of children under the age of five annually.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breastfeeding decreases the risk of respiratory tract infections, ear infections, sudden infant death syndrome (SIDS), and diarrhea for the baby, both in developing and developed countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Other benefits have been proposed to include lower risks of asthma, food allergies, and diabetes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breastfeeding may also improve cognitive development and decrease the risk of obesity in adulthood.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Benefits for the mother include less blood loss following delivery, better contraction of the uterus, and a decreased risk of postpartum depression.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breastfeeding delays the return of menstruation, and in very specific circumstances, fertility, a phenomenon known as lactational amenorrhea.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Long-term benefits for the mother include decreased risk of breast cancer, cardiovascular disease, diabetes, metabolic syndrome, and rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breastfeeding is less expensive than infant formula, but its impact on mothers' ability to earn an income is not usually factored into calculations comparing the two feeding methods.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] It is also common for women to experience symptoms such as: vaginal dryness, De Quervain syndrome, cramping, mastitis, moderate to severe nipple pain, and a general lack of bodily autonomy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] These symptoms generally peak at the start of breastfeeding but disappear or become considerably more manageable after the first few weeks.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Each feeding may last as long as 30–60 minutes, as milk supply develops and the infant learns the Suck-Swallow-Breathe pattern.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] However, as milk supply increases and the infant becomes more efficient at feeding, the duration of feeds may shorten.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] When direct breastfeeding is not possible, expressing or pumping to empty the breasts can help mothers avoid plugged milk ducts and breast infection, maintain their milk supply, resolve engorgement, and provide milk to be fed to their infant at a later time.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Medical conditions that do not allow breastfeeding are rare.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Mothers who take certain recreational drugs should not breastfeed, however, most medications are compatible with breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Available evidence indicates that it is unlikely that COVID-19 can be transmitted through breast milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Smoking tobacco and consuming limited amounts of alcohol or coffee are not reasons to avoid breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breast development starts in puberty with the growth of ducts, fat cells, and connective tissue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The ultimate size of the breasts is determined by the number of fat cells.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The size of the breast is not related to a mother's breastfeeding capability or the volume of milk she can produce.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The process of milk production, termed **lactogenesis**, occurs in 3 stages.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The first stage takes place during pregnancy, allowing for the development of the breast and production of colostrum, the thick, early form of milk that is low in volume but rich in nutrition.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The birth of the baby and the placenta trigger the onset of the second stage of milk production, triggering the milk to come in over the next several days.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The third stage of milk production occurs gradually over several weeks and is characterized by a full milk supply that is regulated locally (at the breast), predominantly by the infant's demand for food.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This differs from the second stage of lactogenesis, which is regulated centrally (in the brain) by hormone feedback loops that naturally occur after the placenta is delivered.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Although traditionally, lactation occurs following pregnancy, lactation may also be induced with hormone therapy and nipple stimulation in the absence of pregnancy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Changes in pregnancy, starting around 16 weeks gestational age, prepare the breast for lactation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] While prolactin is the predominant hormone in milk *production,* progesterone, which is at high levels during pregnancy, blocks the prolactin receptors in the breast, thus inhibiting milk from "coming in" during pregnancy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Many other physiologic changes occur under the control of progesterone and estrogen.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] From about the 16th week of pregnancy, the breasts can begin to produce milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] It's not unusual for small amounts of straw-coloured fluid called colostrum to leak from the nipples during this relatively early stage.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breast development throughout pregnancy may result in significant Areola and Areolar gland enlargement, erectile nipples or nipple sensitivity.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The third stage of labor describes the period between the birth of the baby and the delivery of the placenta, which normally lasts less than 30 minutes.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The delivery of the placenta causes an abrupt drop off of placental hormones.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This drop, specifically in progesterone, allows prolactin to work effectively at its receptors in the breast, leading to an array of changes over the next several days that allow the milk to "come in"; these changes are known collectively as Lactogenesis II.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Colostrum continues to be produced for these next few days, as Lactogenesis II occurs.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Milk may "come in" as late as five days after delivery; however, this process may be delayed due to a number of factors as described in the Process "Delay in milk 'coming in'" subsection below.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Oxytocin, which signals the smooth muscle of the uterus to contract during pregnancy, labor, birth and following delivery, is also involved in the process of breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Oxytocin also contracts the smooth muscle layer of band-like cells surrounding the milk ducts and alveoli to the newly produced milk through the duct system and out through the nipple.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This process is known as the *milk ejection reflex*, or *let-down.* Because of oxytocin's dual activity at the breast and the uterus, breastfeeding mothers may also experience uterine cramping at the time of breastfeeding, for the first several days to weeks.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Prolactin and oxytocin are vital for establishing milk supply initially; however, once the milk supply is well established, the volume and content of the milk produced are controlled locally.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Although prolactin levels are higher on average among breastfeeding mothers, prolactin levels themselves do not correlate to milk volume.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] At this stage, production of milk is triggered by milk drainage from the breasts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The only way to maintain milk supply is to drain the breasts frequently.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Infrequent or incomplete drainage of the breasts, decreases blood flow to the alveoli and signals the milk-producing cells to produce less milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breast pumps are often used to drain the breasts when the infant is not feeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] A condition called Mastitis sometimes occurs in this stage, resulting from incomplete milk drainage.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine recommends against trying to "empty" the breasts, whether through pushing the baby to feed more or through over use of a breast pump, to prevent causing milk oversupply.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The content of breast milk should be discussed in two separate categories: the nutritional content, and the *bioactive content*, i.e., the enzymes, proteins, antibodies, and signaling molecules that assist the infant in ways outside of nutrition.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] At birth, the composition of breast milk corresponds in quality to the specific needs of the infant.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The pattern of intended nutrient content in breast milk is relatively consistent.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breastmilk is made from nutrients in the mother's bloodstream and bodily stores.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] It has an optimal balance of fat, sugar, water, and protein that is needed for a baby's age-appropriate growth and development.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] That being said, a variety of factors can influence the nutritional makeup of breastmilk, including gestational age, age of infant, maternal age, maternal smoking, and nutritional needs of the infant.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The first type of milk produced is called *colostrum*.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The volume of colostrum produced during each feeding is appropriate for the size of the newborn's stomach and is sufficient, calorically, for feeding a newborn during the first few days of life.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Produced during pregnancy and the first days after childbirth, colostrum is rich in protein and Vitamins A, B12 and K, which support infants' growth, brain development, vision, immune systems, red blood cells, and clotting cascade.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The breast milk also has long-chain polyunsaturated fatty acids which help with normal retinal and neural development.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The caloric content of colostrum is about 54 Calories/100mL.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The second type of milk is transitional milk, which is produced during the transition from colostrum to mature breast milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] As the breast milk matures over several weeks, the protein content decreases on average.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The caloric content of breastmilk is reflective of the caloric requirements of the infant, increasing steadily after 12 months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The caloric content of breastmilk in the first 12 months of breastfeeding is approximated to be 58-72 Calories/100mL.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Comparatively, the caloric content after 48 months is approximately 83-129 Calories/100mL.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] When a mother has her full milk supply and is feeding her infant, the first milk to be expressed is called the foremilk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Foremilk is typically thinner and less rich in calories.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The hindmilk that follows is rich in calories and fat.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If the mother is not deficient in vitamins, breast milk normally supplies the baby's needs, except for Vitamin D.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Providing this quantity of Vitamin D to breastfeeding infants has been shown to reduce rates of Vitamin D insufficiency (defined as 25-OH vitamin D < 50 nmol/L).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] However, there was insufficient evidence in the most recent Cochrane Review to determine if this quantity reduced rates of Vitamin D deficiency (defined as 25-OH vitamin D < 30 nmol/L) or rickets.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Term infants typically do not need iron supplementation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Delaying cord clamping at birth for at least one minute improves the infants' iron status for the first year.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] When complementary (solid) foods are introduced at about 6 months of age, parents should make sure to choose iron-rich foods to help maintain their children's iron stores.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In addition to nutritional benefits, breastmilk also provides enzymes, antibodies, and other substances that support the infant's growth and development.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The bioactive makeup of breastmilk also changes based on the needs of the infant; for example, when an infant is recovering from an upper respiratory infection, local signaling allows for increased passage of immune cells and proteins to aid the infant's immune system.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Produced during pregnancy and the first after childbirth, colostrum is easy to digest and has laxative properties that help the infant to pass early stools.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This aids in the excretion of excess bilirubin, which helps to prevent jaundice.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Colostrum also helps to seal the infants gastrointestinal tract from foreign substances and germs, which may sensitize the baby to foods that the mother has eaten and decrease the risk of diarrheal illness.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Although the baby has received some antibodies (IgG) through the placenta, colostrum contains a substance which is new to the newborn, secretory immunoglobulin A (IgA).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] IgA works to attack germs in the mucous membranes of the throat, lungs, and intestines, which are most likely to come under attack from germs.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Additionally, colostrum and mature breast milk contain many antioxidant and anti-inflammatory enzymes and proteins that decrease the risk of gastrointestinal allergies to food, respiratory allergies to air particles like pollen, and other atopic diseases, such as asthma and eczema.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] It is recommended for mothers to initiate breastfeeding within the first hour after birth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Uninterrupted skin-to-skin contact and breastfeeding can begin immediately after birth, and should continue for at least one hour after birth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This period of infant-mother interaction, known generally as kangaroo care, or the "golden hour" during the immediate postpartum period, assists in the mother–child bonding for both mother and baby, and is thought to encourage instinctual breastfeeding behavior in the infant.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Newborns who are immediately placed on their mother's skin have a natural instinct to latch on to the breast and start nursing, typically within one hour of birth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Success with breastfeeding in this "golden hour" increases the likelihood of successful breastfeeding at discharge.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Skin-to-skin mother-baby contact should still occur, even if the baby is born by Cesarean section.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The baby is placed on the mother in the operating room or the recovery area.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If the mother is unable to immediately hold the baby, a family member can provide skin-to-skin care until the mother is able.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] According to studies cited by UNICEF, babies naturally follow a process that leads to a first breastfeed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Shortly after birth, the infant relaxes and makes small movements of the arms, shoulders, and head.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If placed on the mother's abdomen, the baby gradually inches towards the breast, known as the breast crawl and begins to feed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] After feeding, it is normal for a baby to remain latched to the breast while resting.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This is sometimes mistaken for a lack of appetite.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Without interruptions, all babies follow this process.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Rushing, by picking up and moving the infant to the breast, or interrupting the process, such as removing the baby to be weighed, may complicate subsequent feeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Activities such as weighing, measuring, bathing, needle-sticks, and eye prophylaxis wait until after the first feeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] These late preterm (34 weeks –36 weeks and 6 days) and early term (37 weeks–38 weeks and 6 days) infants are at increased risk for both breastfeeding cessation and complications of insufficient milk intake (e.g., dehydration, hypoglycemia, jaundice, and excessive weight loss).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] They are often expected to feed like term babies, but they have less strength and stamina to feed adequately.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] By convention, such children are often fed on expressed breast milk or other supplementary feeds through tubes, supplemental nursing systems, bottles, spoons, or cups until they develop a satisfactory ability to suck and swallow breast milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Frequent breastfeeding or small amounts of supplementation may be needed for successful outcomes; breast pumping or hand expression is often helpful in providing adequate stimulation to the mother's breasts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Starting to breastfeed may be challenging for mothers of preterm infants, especially those born before 34 weeks, because their breasts may still be developing (in Lactogenesis I, see Breastfeeding Physiology).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Additionally, mother–infant separation and the stressful environment of the NICU are also barriers to breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Availability of a lactation specialist in the NICU can be helpful for mothers trying to establish their milk supply.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Additionally, skin-to-skin (Kangaroo Care) is safe and beneficial to both mother and baby.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Kangaroo Care stabilizes newborn premature infants' vital signs, such as their heart rate, providing a naturally warm environment that helps them regulate their temperature.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] It is also beneficial to the mother, as it may improve the development of milk supply and be beneficial for mental health.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Newborn babies usually breastfeed 8 to 12 times every 24 hours, and they typically express hunger cues every one to three hours for the first two to four weeks of their lives.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] A newborn has a small stomach capacity, approximately 20 mL.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The amount of breast milk that is produced is timed to meet the infant's needs in that the first milk, colostrum, is concentrated but produced in only very small amounts, gradually increasing in volume to meet the expanding size of the infant's stomach capacity.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Cluster feeding may occur for several months, whereby infants will feed very frequently (every 30 minutes to 1 hour), usually associated with developmental milestones.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Many newborns typically feed for 10 to 15 minutes on each breast; however, feeds may last up to 45 minutes, depending on the infant's alertness and efficiency.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Parents need to recognize the difference between Nutritive and Non-Nutritive Sucking.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Nutritive Sucking follows a slow, rhythmic pattern, with one to two sucks per swallow.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Non-nutritive sucking is a faster-paced sucking pattern with few swallows.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This swallow pattern is often observed at the beginning or the end of a feed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] At the beginning of the feed, this pattern triggers milk letdown, while at the end of the feed, this may signal that the infant is tired or becoming relaxed with a slower milk velocity.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] After solids are introduced at around six months of age, continued breastfeeding is recommended.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends that babies be breastfed at least until 12 months, or longer if both the mother and child wish.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The World Health Organization's guidelines recommend "continue[d] frequent, on-demand breastfeeding until two years of age or beyond.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Extended breastfeeding means breastfeeding after the age of 12 or 24 months, depending on the source.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In Western countries such as the United States, Canada, and Great Britain, extended breastfeeding is relatively uncommon and can provoke criticism.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In the United States, 22.4% of babies are breastfed for 12 months, the minimum time advised by the American Academy of Pediatrics.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In India, mothers commonly breastfeed for 2 to 3 years.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Supplementation is defined as the use of additional milk or fluid products to feed an infant, in addition to breastmilk, during the first 6 months of life.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine recommends only supplementing when medically indicated, as opposed to mixing use of formula and breastmilk for reasons that are not necessarily medical indications.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Some medical indications for supplementation include low blood sugar, dehydration, excessive weight loss or poor gain, and jaundice in the infant; true low milk supply; severe nipple pain unrelieved by interventions; and medical contraindications to breastfeeding, as described below.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Supplements can be delivered at the breast through a supplemental nursing system to stimulate the production of the mother's own milk and to preserve the breastfeeding relationship.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Some parents may desire to supplement proactively if early signs of insufficient intake, such as decreased urination, dry mucous membranes, or persistent signs of hunger, are noticed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If these signs are noticed, it is important to have the mother-infant dyad evaluated by a breastfeeding specialist or pediatrician to determine the true cause of the symptoms and determine the need for supplementation.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Often, these symptoms are caused by poor milk transfer at the breast and can be solved with adjustments to the latch.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Occasionally, they may be caused by other processes, unrelated to breastfeeding, so evaluation is necessary.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Supplementation with formula is associated with decreased rates of exclusive breastfeeding at 6 months, and overall decreased length of breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In terms of *what* to supplement with, the first choice is always the mother's own breastmilk, save any medical contraindications to its use.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The second best option for supplementation is pasteurized human donor milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Finally, specific formulas may be used for supplementation if maternal or donor breastmilk is not an option.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] One situation where this may be the case is in cases of infant metabolic diseases, such as galactosemia.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine recommends that supplementation only be used when medically indicated and when overseen by a medical professional, such as a pediatrician or family physician, and after consultation with an IBCLC.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Without sufficient breast stimulation, supplementation can reduce the mother's milk production, so pumping would be indicated in these cases if continued breastfeeding is desired.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Indications for use of donor breastmilk are very closely outlined by the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Effective positioning and technique for latching on are necessary to prevent nipple soreness and allow the baby to obtain enough milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Babies can successfully latch on to the breast from multiple positions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Each baby may prefer a particular position.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The "football" hold places the baby's legs next to the mother's side with the baby facing the mother.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Using the "cradle" or "cross-body" hold, the mother supports the baby's head in the crook of her arm.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The "cross-over" hold is similar to the cradle hold, except that the mother supports the baby's head with the opposite hand.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The mother may choose a reclining position on her back or side with the baby lying next to her.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] To help with breastfeeding, some people use a nursing pillow.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] No matter the position the parent-infant dyad finds most comfortable, there are a few components of every position that will help facilitate a successful latch.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The mother should be comfortable while breastfeeding, and should have her back, feet, and arms supported with pillows as necessary.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Additionally, when starting the latch process, the infant should be aligned with their abdomen facing their mother, which can be remembered as "tummy-to-mummy," and with their hips, shoulders, and head aligned.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This alignment helps to facilitate proper, efficient swallowing mechanics.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Latching refers to how the baby uses their lips, cheek, and tongue to attach to the nipple and breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Sebaceous glands called Glands of Montgomery located in the areola secrete an oily fluid that lubricates and protects the nipple during latching.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The visible portions of the glands can be seen on the skin's surface as small, round bumps.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The rooting reflex is the baby's natural tendency to turn towards the breast with the mouth open wide.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] When preparing to latch, mothers should make use of this reflex by gently stroking the baby's philtrum, the area between the upper lip and the nose, with their nipple to induce the baby to open their mouth with a wide gape.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] One way to help the infant achieve a deep latch is to compress the breast tissue into a "U" or "hamburger shape," so that the infant can fit the breast tissue into their mouth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This is done by the mother placing her thumb and fingers in line with the infant's nose and mouth, respectively, and using this grip to compress the breast tissue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If the newborn seems to need help in latching on, the mother should focus on helping the infant by bringing their chin to the breast first.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This facilitates a deep, asymmetric latch, and also helps the infant extend their neck and tilt their forehead back to maintain this deep latch and ease the swallowing process.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In a good latch, a large amount of the areola, in addition to the nipple, is in the baby's mouth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The amount of areola visible on either side of the infant's mouth should be **asymmetric**, meaning most of the "bottom" of the areola should be in the infant's mouth, and much more of the "top" of the areola should be visible.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This position helps point the nipple toward the roof of the infant's mouth, helping the infant recruit more milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The neck should be extended to facilitate swallowing, and as such, the chin will be close to the breast, and the forehead and nose should be far from the breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Another sign of a good latch is the contour of the infant's cheeks; the cheeks should be rounded all the way to the edge of the mouth, rather than dimpled or creased at the edge of the mouth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This is a good indicator of effective suck mechanics.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Additionally, to achieve a deep latch, the infant's mouth must be open wide, preferably wider than 140 degrees.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In a poor, shallow latch, the infant may latch close to, or at, the nipple, which can cause the mother pain.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] While the infant is at the breast, the first indicators of a shallow latch are having the areola be largely visible outside the infant's mouth and a narrow infant mouth angle.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Additional signs result from poor positioning when the infant comes toward the breast to latch.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If the infant leads with their brow or forehead, they are likely to flex their neck; this latching mechanism causes the nipple to point down and then hit the hard palate during sucking.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] From an external view, this manifests as the nose and forehead being close to the breast and the chin far from the breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This neck flexion also obstructs the normal swallowing mechanism, preventing the infant from drinking efficiently.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] When the baby suckles, muscles in the breast squeeze milk towards the nipples.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Some women report they do not experience anything, while others report a tingling sensation, which is sometimes described as quite strong.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The baby may be seen to respond to the start of milk flow by changing from quick sucks to deep rhythmic swallows.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Sometimes the let-down is so strong that the baby splutters and coughs, and the mother may need to remove the baby from her breast for a short time until the flow becomes less forceful.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Milk may also let down unexpectedly when a mother hears her baby cry or even only thinks about the baby.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Nursing pads may be made or purchased to absorb unexpected milk flows.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Infants of mothers with inverted nipples can still achieve a good latch with perhaps a little extra effort.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] For some women, the nipple may easily become erect when stimulated.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Other women may require modified breastfeeding techniques, and some may need extra devices, such as nipple shells, modified syringes, or breast pumps to expose the nipple.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] La Leche League and Toronto Public Health offer several techniques to use during pregnancy or even in the early days following birth that may help to bring a flat or inverted nipple out.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The World Health Organization's Ten Steps to Successful Breastfeeding recommends total avoidance of pacifiers for breastfeeding infants.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In 2016, a large review of studies reported that the use of a pacifier beginning at birth or after lactation was established did not significantly affect the duration of exclusive and partial breastfeeding up to four months of age.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The CDC, however, currently (2022) reports that early use of pacifiers can have a negative outcome on the success of breastfeeding, and they suggest that it should be delayed until breastfeeding is firmly established.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Ankyloglossia, also called "tongue-tie" may cause shallow latch, poor milk transfer, and other problems with breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If it is determined that the inability to latch on properly is related to ankyloglossia, a simple surgical procedure to clip the frenulum can correct the condition.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine and the Australian Dental Association have raised concern over the growing trend of oral tie surgeries, due to evidence for benefit being low-quality, inconsistent, or unsupported.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Engorgement is the swelling and stretching of the breast tissue due to the accumulation of fluid in the tissue surrounding and supporting the milk-producing cells and ducts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Engorgement most frequently occurs as milk "comes in" and during the weaning process.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] As milk is coming in, several processes occur.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] At the end of pregnancy, the blood vessels that supply the breast dilate, allowing for leaking into the tissue or interstitial space.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Additionally, the birth of an infant is followed by massive fluid shifts to both offload excess fluid, which had been used to supply oxygen and nutrients to the fetus through the placenta, which is no longer needed, and supply additional fluid to the breasts to start the process of making milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] These fluid shifts often result in some of this excess fluid leaking into the breast tissue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Finally, milk "coming in" can create an uncomfortably full feeling, which, combined with the aforementioned fluid accumulation in the breast tissue, can cause severe pain.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If breastfeeding is suddenly stopped, the breasts are likely to become engorged.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Pumping small amounts to relieve discomfort helps to train the breasts to produce less milk gradually.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] There is presently no safe medication to prevent engorgement, but cold compresses and ibuprofen may help to relieve pain and swelling.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Pain should go away with emptying of the breasts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If symptoms persist and comfort measures are not helpful, a blocked milk duct or infection may be present, and the affected person should seek medical intervention.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Although very common, nipple pain and nipple trauma (cracking, open sores) should not be normalized, as these are often signs of a shallow latch or other underlying problem that can be evaluated and fixed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In addition to shallow latch, other causes of nipple pain include, but are not limited to, skin infection or inflammation, blood vessel spasm or the equivalent of Raynaud Syndrome in the breast, mastitis, plugged ducts, and nipple blebs.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Pain caused by a problem deep in the breast may also present with nipple pain due to the paths of nerves in the breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] In addition to the serious nature of many of these causes, nipple pain is a common reason for a mother stopping breastfeeding, so mothers experiencing nipple pain must be evaluated.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] While milk normally "comes in" by 3 days after birth, there are several reasons this may be delayed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Risk factors for this delay include maternal diabetes, stressful delivery, retained placenta, prolonged labor and birth by C-section.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Mothers experiencing a delay in their milk coming in should consult with a lactation specialist and their pediatrician, as they may need to supplement with donor milk or formula to help the infant gain weight and pump to encourage milk to come in sooner and in greater volume.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breast milk supply increases in response to the baby's demand for milk and decreases when milk is allowed to remain in the breasts.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] When considering a possibly low milk supply, it is important to consider the difference between "perceived low milk supply" and "true low milk supply".
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Perceived low milk supply occurs when mothers, for a variety of reasons, believe that they are not making enough milk to feed their infant.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] These reasons may include fussiness, colic, preference for the bottle as opposed to the breast, long nursing duration, decreased sensation of breast fullness, and even decreased frequency of infant stools.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] However, in these cases, it is important to reassure the parent that infant weight gain is absolute proof of adequate milk intake.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Thus, if the infant is breastfeeding exclusively and is gaining weight appropriately, then the parent can be reassured that they are producing enough milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] True low milk supply can be either *primary* (caused by medical conditions or anatomical issues in the mother), *secondary* (caused by not thoroughly and regularly removing milk from the breasts), or both.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Primary causes may manifest before or during pregnancy, during labor, and even after birth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Secondary causes are far more common than primary ones.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] One study found that 15% of healthy first-time mothers had low milk supply 2–3 weeks after birth, with secondary causes accounting for at least two-thirds of those cases.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Poor milk intake is signaled by poor infant weight gain, signs of dehydration, and hypoglycemia.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Poor milk intake can be caused by poor milk transfer by the infant or by true low milk supply by the mother.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] When the milk "comes in" appropriately, but is followed by decreased milk supply, this is most often caused by allowing milk to remain in the breasts for long periods of time, or insufficiently draining the breasts during feeds.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If the baby is latching and swallowing well (signs of good milk transfer), but is not gaining weight as expected or is showing signs of dehydration, low milk supply in the mother can be suspected, and a lactation specialist should be consulted.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] More than 80% of newborns develop jaundice within several days of birth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Jaundice, or yellowing of the skin and eyes, occurs when bilirubin, a byproduct of the breakdown/recycling of red blood cells, builds up in the newborn's bloodstream faster than the liver can break it down and excrete it through the baby's urine and stool.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] By continuing to breastfeed frequently (start at 8-12 times per day), the infant's body can usually rid itself of the bilirubin excess by encouraging more urine and stool production.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] However, in some cases, the infant may need additional treatments, such as UV light therapy or additional feedings (see Supplementation) to keep the condition from progressing into more severe problems.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] There are two types of newborn jaundice related to breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breastfeeding jaundice is quite common and may occur in the first week of life in conjunction with ongoing weight loss.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The cause is thought to be low caloric intake.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Formula-fed infants tend to lose less weight after birth compared to breastfed infants, supporting the hypothesis that breastfeeding jaundice is related to caloric intake rather than volume intake.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Individual risk factors, such as breastfeeding, are not *predictive* of developing severe jaundice: Breastfeeding is a risk factor for severely high levels of bilirubin, but the risk factor is very common, and the risk of severely high bilirubin remains small.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breast milk jaundice is jaundice that persists despite appropriate weight gain.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] This type of jaundice may start as breastfeeding jaundice and persist, or may not appear until after the baby has begun to gain weight, typically around 4–5 days old.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] It often persists beyond the second and third weeks of life.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] There is no single cause of breast milk jaundice; rather, the causes are multifactorial and frequently debated in the literature.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The causes of breast milk jaundice include variations in bilirubin metabolism, genetic variations, and variations in breastmilk, including the harmless and helpful germs found naturally on the surface of the skin and in the breastmilk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breast milk jaundice is usually not a reason to stop nursing.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Weaning is the process of replacing breast milk with other foods; the infant is fully weaned after the replacement is complete.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Psychological factors affect the weaning process for both mother and infant, as issues of closeness and separation are very prominent.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Unless a medical emergency necessitates abruptly stopping breastfeeding, it is best to gradually increase the period between feedings or eliminate feedings to allow the breasts to adjust to the decreased demands without becoming engorged.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Studies show that a large number of women discontinue breastfeeding early due to lack of working place support for breastfeeding mothers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] La Leche League advises parents to shift their children's focus at bedtime away from breastfeeding, as it is often the most difficult feeding for them to let go.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If weaning starts at 12 months or later, it is not necessary to switch to infant formula or "toddler formula" as is sold commercially.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] At 12 months, it is recommended that the baby be switched to whole cow's milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Reduced-fat or skim milk generally is not appropriate before age 2 because it lacks sufficient fat or calories to promote early brain development.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] If the mother was experiencing lactational amenorrhea, periods will begin to return with weaning, along with restored fertility.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Extended breastfeeding usually means breastfeeding beyond the age of 12 to 24 months, depending on the culture.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The American Academy of Family Physicians states that "health outcomes for mothers and babies are best when breastfeeding continues for at least two years.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breast milk is known to contain lactoferrin (Lf), which protects the infant from infection caused by a wide range of pathogens.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] The amount of Lf in breast milk is lactation-stage related.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] One study evaluated Lf concentration in prolonged lactation from the first to the 48th month postpartum.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] It was found to be at the highest level in colostrum, dropped to the lowest level during 1 – 12 months of lactation, and then increased significantly during the 13–24 months of lactation, close to the Lf concentration in colostrum.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] At over 24 months, the level dropped, though not significantly.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Lactation consultants are trained to assist mothers in preventing and solving breastfeeding difficulties such as sore nipples and low milk supply.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] They commonly work in hospitals, physician or midwife practices, public health programs, and private practice.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Lactation consultants earn their credential, International Board Certified Lactation Consultant (IBCLC), through the International Board of Lactation Consultant Examiners.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Breastfeeding support from a lactation consultant is associated with higher rates of any breastfeeding at 6 months but not at 1 month or 3 months post pregnancy based on a meta-analysis of studies conducted in the US and Canada.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p01] Peer support for breastfeeding is associated with higher rates of any breastfeeding at 1 month and 3 to 6 months and of exclusive breastfeeding at 1 month, but it is unrelated to breastfeeding outcomes past 6 months post-pregnancy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Medical conditions that do not allow breastfeeding are fairly rare.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Infants that are otherwise healthy uniformly benefit from breastfeeding, however, extra precautions should be taken or breastfeeding avoided in circumstances including certain infectious diseases and medical conditions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] A breastfeeding child can become infected with HIV.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Factors such as the mother's viral load complicate breastfeeding recommendations for HIV-positive mothers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] They also recommend that national authorities in each country decide which infant feeding practice should be promoted by their maternal and child health services to avoid transmitting HIV from mother to child.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] However, the CDC continues to recommend against HIV-positive mothers breastfeeding in the United States.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Infant formula should only be given if this can be safely done.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Human T-Lymphotrophic Virus (HTLV) is able to be passed through breastmilk from mother to child.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The worldwide rate of transmission through breastmilk is estimated to be 3.9–27%, and this risk is increased by high maternal viral load and prolonged periods of breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Current data demonstrates that while breastfeeding for less than six months does not, independently, increase risk of HTLV-1 transmission, not breastfeeding during that time *does* decrease risk of transmission.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] As such, CDC recommends against breastfeeding when mothers have HTLV Types I or II.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Recognizing the importance of breastfeeding in more resource-poor areas of the world, the World Health Organization recommends shortening the duration of breastfeeding, or avoiding breastfeeding where possible.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Mothers with Marburg virus or Ebola should not breastfeed their infants or feed them with expressed breastmilk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Infants whose mothers have suspected untreated tuberculosis (TB) should be isolated from their mothers to reduce the risk of transmission.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] As such, these infants should not be breastfed during this time and until the mother has been treated appropriately for 2 weeks and is no longer contagious.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] However, these infants may be fed expressed breastmilk from their mother.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Transmission of TB through breastmilk, without an isolated breast infection caused by the Tuberculosis bacteria (*Mycobacterium tuberculosis*), has never been documented in the scientific literature.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Mothers who do have an isolated breast infection caused by *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, termed **tuberculous mastitis**, should not feed their infants with their own breastmilk, even if it is fed by bottle.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Herpes simplex virus (HSV) is the virus that causes genital herpes and oral cold sores, and it can be very dangerous to infants.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The CDC advises to continue breastfeeding if there are no open/active lesions on the breast and other lesions covered.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Varicella zoster is the virus responsible for chickenpox and shingles (also known as herpes zoster).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The CDC advises that breastfeeding is safe to continue as long as the breasts are clear of lesions, also emphasizing that if pumping or hand expressing milk, proper hand-hygiene should be used to minimize transfer.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] In May 2020, WHO and UNICEF stressed that the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic was not a reason to discontinue breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] They recommend that women continue to breastfeed during the pandemic, even if they have confirmed or suspected COVID-19, because evidence indicates that it is unlikely that COVID-19 can be transmitted through breast milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] A study published in 2021 found that, while SARS-CoV-2 RNA may be found in some samples of breastmilk from recently infected mothers, the breastmilk does not contain infectious virus and is not considered a transmission risk factor.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Mothers who have suspected or confirmed diagnoses of COVID-19 should thoroughly wash their hands and wear a well-fitting mask before breastfeeding their infant, or express breastmilk and feed the infant by bottle.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Moderate alcohol consumption by breastfeeding mothers can significantly affect infants.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Even one or two drinks, including beer, may reduce milk intake by 20 to 23%, leading to increased agitation and poor sleep patterns.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Regular heavy drinking (more than two drinks daily) can shorten breastfeeding duration and cause issues in infants, such as excessive sedation, fluid retention, and hormonal imbalances.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Additionally, higher alcohol consumption may negatively impact children's academic achievement.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] When breastfeeding, alcohol may be consumed in moderation and does not require "Pumping-and-Dumping" (pumping and discarding breastmilk).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Alcohol crosses from the blood to the breastmilk by diffusion.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Thus, the concentration of alcohol in the breastmilk is approximately equal to the concentration in the maternal bloodstream at any given time.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] As the mother's liver processes the alcohol, more and more alcohol is pulled out of the breastmilk and back into the bloodstream.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Thus, it is suggested to wait 2 hours after drinking before nursing or pumping.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] In the case of infrequent binge drinking, it has been shown that infants consume through breastmilk only a fraction of the alcohol their mothers have ingested.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] While a minute, clinically insignificant amount of alcohol may be absorbed into the infant's bloodstream, it is unlikely that this amount would cause any noticeable cognitive or neuromotor effects.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The data on the use of marijuana during breastfeeding is limited; however, in part due to our lack of knowledge in this area, the CDC recommends against using marijuana or marijuana-containing products, including CBD, during breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The main active ingredient in marijuana, tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), can be found in breastmilk anywhere from six days to more than six weeks after marijuana use.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] There is limited data on the long term effects of this exposure on the infant, however some studies have voiced concern regarding delayed motor development in infants exposed to THC.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Mothers who smoke or use other tobacco products can breastfeed their infants, according to La Leche League, the CDC, and the Royal Women's Hospital (Australia).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] However, maternal tobacco use may decrease milk supply.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Additionally, tobacco smoking, regardless of feeding method, increases risk of SIDS and respiratory illnesses.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Thus, attempting to decrease tobacco use or even cease helps to minimize tobacco exposure to infants and maximize the benefits of breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Tobacco cessation products, such as nicotine patches and other medications, like bupropion, are able to be used by breastfeeding mothers.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Mothers utilizing recreational drugs, such as cocaine, methamphetamines, PCP, and heroin, should not breastfeed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Most medications are compatible with continued breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Many medicines pass into breastmilk in small amounts; however, very few medications actually reach the infant and are absorbed in a way that would actually impact the infant.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Several characteristics of medications, including size and pH of the medication molecule and how well the medication is absorbed in the GI tract, influence how much of a medication may reach, and may ultimately be absorbed, by the infant.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] In addition to the effects on the infant, many medications are known to significantly suppress milk production, including pseudoephedrine, diuretics, and contraceptives that contain estrogen.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] There are several resources to assist medical professionals in determining which medications are safe for pregnancy and breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] While patients can use these resources, they are targeted toward medical professionals.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Patients should be encouraged to consult a lactation specialist or a medical provider trained in breastfeeding medicine if any concerns arise.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] "Pumping-and-dumping" is the concept of expressing breastmilk and discarding it due to a medication or substance "tainting" the breastmilk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] It was once believed that drinking alcohol or taking any medications, even medicines like ibuprofen, required pumping-and-dumping.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Pumping-and-dumping, or stopping breastfeeding altogether, is only required in very rare circumstances, such as with radioactive medications or chemotherapy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] If a parent is concerned with a possible milk contaminant, they can express and save the breastmilk until they can consult with a lactation specialist or another medical professional trained in breastfeeding medicine.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Galactosemia is a metabolic disorder that prevents the infant from breaking down galactose, which is one of the two components of lactose, a type of sugar found in milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Lactose is also found in breastmilk, so infants with galactosemia should not breastfeed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] A mother may *express* milk (remove milk from breasts) for storage and later use.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Expression may occur manually with hand expression or by using a breast pump.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Mothers express milk for multiple reasons.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Expressing breast milk can maintain a mother's milk supply when mother and child are apart.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] A sick baby who is unable to nurse can take expressed milk through a nasogastric tube.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Some babies are unable or unwilling to nurse.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Maternal breastmilk is the food of choice for premature babies; these infants may be fed maternal milk through tubes, supplemental nursing systems, bottles, spoons, or cups until they develop satisfactory ability to suck and swallow breast milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Some women donate expressed breast milk (EBM) to others, either directly or through a milk bank.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] This allows mothers who cannot breastfeed to give their baby the benefits of breast milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] While informally-shared breastmilk does carry the nutritional benefits of breastmilk, this breastmilk is most often not pasteurized or screened, and thus carries with it the risk of transmitting diseases or medications that are unsafe for infants.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Parents considering directed or informal milk sharing should discuss this option with their doctor, and they should be familiar with the donor's medical history and milk handling practices.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Use of informally-shared (unscreened, not pasteurized) milk from an anonymous donor is discouraged by the Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Babies feed differently with artificial nipples than from a breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] With the breast, the infant's tongue massages the milk out rather than sucking, and the nipple does not go as far into the mouth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Drinking from a bottle takes less effort, and the milk may come more quickly, potentially causing the baby to lose desire for the breast.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] This is often referred to as *nipple confusion* or *nipple preference*.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] While some infants do experience this preference for the bottle, many infants do not and will be able to alternate between bottle and breast without issue.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] "Exclusively expressing" and "exclusively pumping" are terms for a mother who exclusively feeds a baby expressed milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Exclusively pumping is poorly studied in the literature, especially in recent years.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] However, from available evidence, it appears fairly uncommon, with only approximately 7% of study participants reporting exclusive pumping.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Breastmilk may be stored for various amounts of time depending on storage temperature and conditions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The content and quality of expressed milk change over time as it is stored, particularly when frozen.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] For example, there is a decrease in the ability of breastmilk to kill bacteria when it is stored in the refrigerator for more than 48 hours.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Additionally, the quantity of fat, protein, and calories in breastmilk decreases when the milk is frozen for more than 3 months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] While several components of breastmilk change over time, inflammatory factors (cytokines) and maternal antibodies, and growth factors are thought to be stable for at least 6 months when the breastmilk is frozen.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Storage guidelines, according to the CDC, La Leche League International and the Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine, are noted in the table below.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Expressed breastmilk can be stored in freezer storage bags, containers made specifically for breastmilk, a supplemental nursing system, or a bottle ready for use.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Parents should avoid using storage containers which contain bisphenol A (BPA).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Additionally, use of polyethylene containers have been shown to decrease the immune benefits of breastmilk, including its ability to kill bacteria and the maternal antibodies it contains, by up to 60%.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] It is not only a mother who may breastfeed a child.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Parents may hire another person to do so (a wet nurse), or may share childcare with another mother (cross-nursing).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Both of these were common throughout history.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] It remains popular in some developing nations, including those in Africa, for more than one woman to breastfeed a child.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Shared breastfeeding is a risk factor for HIV infection in infants.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Shared nursing can sometimes provoke negative social reactions in the English-speaking world.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] A mother can continue breastfeeding an older sibling while also breastfeeding a new baby; this is called *tandem nursing*.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] During the late stages of pregnancy, the milk changes to colostrum.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] While some children continue to breastfeed even with this change, others may wean.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Most mothers can produce enough milk for tandem nursing, but the new baby should be nursed first for at least the first few days after delivery to ensure it receives enough colostrum.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Breastfeeding triplets or larger broods is a challenge given babies' varying appetites.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Breasts can respond to the demand and produce larger milk quantities; mothers have breastfed triplets successfully.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Re-lactation is the process of restarting breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] In developing countries, mothers may restart breastfeeding after a weaning as part of an oral rehydration treatment for diarrhea.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] In developed countries, re-lactation is common after early medical problems are resolved, or because a mother changes her mind about breastfeeding.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Re-lactation is most easily accomplished with a newborn or with a baby that was previously breastfeeding; if the baby was initially bottle-fed, the baby may refuse to suckle.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] If the mother has recently stopped breastfeeding, chances are higher that the milk supply will return and be adequate.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Although some mothers successfully re-lactate after months-long interruptions, success is higher for shorter interruptions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Techniques to promote lactation include frequent attempts to breastfeed, extensive skin-to-skin contact with the baby, and frequent, long pumping sessions.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Suckling may be encouraged with a tube filled with infant formula, so that the baby associates suckling at the breast with food.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] A dropper or syringe without the needle may be used to place milk onto the breast while the baby suckles.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The mother should allow the infant to suckle at least ten times during 24 hours, and more times if the baby is interested.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] These times can include every two hours, whenever the baby seems interested, longer at each breast, and when the baby is sleepy, when they might suckle more readily.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] In keeping with increasing contact between mother and child, including increasing skin-to-skin contact, grandmothers should pull back and help in other ways.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Later on, grandmothers can again provide more direct care for the infant.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] These techniques require the mother's commitment over a period of weeks or months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] However, even when lactation is established, the supply may not be large enough to breastfeed exclusively.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] A supportive social environment improves the likelihood of success.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] As the mother's milk production increases, other feeding can decrease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Parents and other family members should watch the baby's weight gain and urine output to assess nutritional adequacy.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] A WHO manual for physicians and senior health workers, citing a 1992 source, states: "If a baby has been breastfeeding sometimes, the breastmilk supply increases in a few days.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Induced lactation, also called *adoptive lactation*, is the process of starting breastfeeding in a woman who did not give birth.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] This usually requires the adoptive mother to take hormones and other drugs to stimulate breast development and promote milk production.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] In some cultures, breastfeeding an adoptive child creates milk kinship that builds community bonds across class and other hierarchical bonds.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Breastfeeding support is universal among major health and children's organizations.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Breastfeeding is associated with a lowered risk of several diseases in both mothers and babies.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Comparing infants that were exclusively breastfed for at least 3 months with never-breastfed infants, the American Academy of Pediatrics reported that in the first year of life breastfed babies averaged about $400 in savings of health care costs.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Infants who are not breastfed are at mildly increased risk of developing lower respiratory infection, ear infections, bacteremia, bacterial meningitis, botulism, urinary tract infection and necrotizing enterocolitis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Breastfeeding may protect against sudden infant death syndrome, insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus, Crohn's disease, ulcerative colitis, childhood lymphoma, allergic diseases, digestive diseases, obesity, and childhood leukemia.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] It is hard however to distinguish the importance of breastfeeding per se and other correlated socioeconomic factors (breastfeeding is more frequent in richer families with higher educations).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Comparing breastfed and non-breastfed siblings in a given family drastically decreases the association between breastfeeding and long-term child well-being.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The average breastfed baby doubles its birth weight in 5–6 months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] By one year, a typical breastfed baby weighs about 2+1⁄2 times its birth weight.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] At one year, breastfed babies tend to be leaner than formula-fed babies, which improves long-term health.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The Davis Area Research on Lactation, Infant Nutrition and Growth (DARLING) study reported that breastfed and formula-fed groups had similar weight gain during the first 3 months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Breastfed babies began to drop below the median beginning at 6 to 8 months and were significantly lower in weight than the formula-fed group between 6 and 18 months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Length gain and head circumference values were similar between groups, suggesting that the breastfed babies were leaner.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Breast milk contains several anti-infective factors such as bile salt stimulated lipase (protecting against amoebic infections) and lactoferrin (which binds to iron and inhibits the growth of intestinal bacteria).
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Exclusive breastfeeding until six months of age helps to protect an infant from gastrointestinal infections in both developing and industrialized countries.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The risk of death due to diarrhea and other infections increases when babies are either partially breastfed or not breastfed at all.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Infants who are exclusively breastfed for the first six months are less likely to die of gastrointestinal infections than infants who switched from exclusive to partial breastfeeding at three to four months.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] During breastfeeding, approximately 0.25–0.5 grams per day of secretory IgA antibodies pass to the baby via milk.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] This is one of the important features of colostrum.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The main target for these antibodies are probably microorganisms in the baby's intestine.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The rest of the body displays some uptake of IgA, but this amount is relatively small.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Maternal vaccinations while breastfeeding are safe for almost all vaccines.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Additionally, the mother's immunity obtained by vaccination against tetanus, diphtheria, whooping cough, and influenza can protect the baby from these diseases, and breastfeeding can reduce the fever rate after infant immunization.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] However, smallpox and yellow fever vaccines increase the risk of infants developing vaccinia and encephalitis.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Several studies have suggested that breast milk can pass antibodies to the infant for as long as the child continues to nurse.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The antibodies may be in the mother's system as a result of being ill, or they may be acquired by drinking milk from a mother who has recently been vaccinated for a particular disease.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] One small study done on nursing mothers who had received the COVID-19 vaccine found that breastmilk continued to contain antibodies for as long as 80 days after receiving the vaccine.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] The World Health Organization reports that babies who receive no breast milk are almost six times more likely to die by the age of one month than those who are partially or fully breastfed.
[src:baby-friendly-hospital-initiative/breastfeeding-p02] Access to healthcare is the single critical determinant of survival or death for the infant.
